<DOCNO> XIE19980611.0002 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Severe Cyclone Hits West India, Killing 283 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, June 10 (Xinhua) -- At least 283 people were
reportedly killed and more than 500 others injured in a severe
cyclonic storm which hit west coast of India Tuesday, according to
reports reaching here.
</P>
<P>
The cyclone, which entered the coastal city of Porbandar,
Gujarat State, around 10:30 a.m. Tuesday and weakened Wednesday
morning, left unprecedented trail of destruction and paralyzed
life in the hit areas.
</P>
<P>
Hundreds of houses were damaged and road and communication
links snapped at several places in the states of Gujarat,
Maharashtra and Rajasthan in the storm which run at the speed of
70 to 150 kilometers per hour.
</P>
<P>
Civil authorities, assisted by the army and air force
personnel, began a massive relief and rescue operations in Gujarat
which was hit the most with 213 killed and over 100 still missing.
</P>
<P>
Indian Minister of State for Agriculture Sompal said here today
in the parliament that crisis management system at the national
level had been activated and the union government maintained a
close contact with the three state governments.
</P>
<P>
The minister informed the parliament that the second
installment of 290.3 million rupees (some 7.25 million U.S.
dollars) was released Wednesday in advance.
</P>
<P>
The first installment of central share of calamity relief fund
of 804.4 million rupees (about 20.1 million dollars) for the
current year had already been released in April. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980611.0003 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> OAU Summit Ends Committed to Stronger Africa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OUAGADOUGOU, June 10 (Xinhua) -- African leaders Wednesday
concluded the 34th summit of the Organization of African Unity
(OAU) after adopting the Ouagadougou declaration and decisions on
the political and economic situation in Africa.
</P>
<P>
A decision on the African Economic Community (AEC),
inaugurated last year to promote continental integration, was
also adopted at the three-day summit, which was dominated by the
escalating conflict between Ethiopia and Eritrea.
</P>
<P>
The conflict has caused grave concern from President Blaise
Compaore of Burkina Faso, who was elected executive chairman of
OAU at the opening of the summit, as well as from the leaders
present at the occasion.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the closing ceremony, Compaore urged the two
countries to follow the recommendations made by the OAU council
of ministers to "put to an end to all hostilities at the same
time and simultaneously."
</P>
<P>
The two countries should seek a peaceful solution to the
conflict through dialog, said Compaore, who also urged Guinea
Bissau to maintain national security and stability.
</P>
<P>
There could be all losers in situation of conflict and
instability, he added.
</P>
<P>
The OAU chairman then called on member states to contribute to
enhancing the effectiveness of the central organ of the
continental body's conflict prevention, management and resolution
mechanism.
</P>
<P>
On the economic front, Compaore said leaders to the summit had
exchanged views and decided to step up the pace of the
continent's integration by bringing into full play the role of
AEC and through close cooperation between AEC and other regional
economic organizations.
</P>
<P>
The leaders had renewed their commitment to a stronger Africa
in the next century, he stated.
</P>
<P>
The structural reforms of the 35-year OAU also became the
focus of attention at the summit.
</P>
<P>
According to Compaore, the organization should be streamlined
to suit the current world situation when great changes have taken
place since its establishment in 1963.
</P>
<P>
Denis Sassou Nguesso, president of the Republic of Congo, also
delivered a speech at the closing ceremony, expressing the common
desire for peace and development of his country and the African
continent as a whole.
</P>
<P>
It was announced the next OAU summit would be held in Algeria
in June 1999. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
