<BODY>
<HEADLINE> More Germany Companies Predicted to Go Bankrupt in 1998 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, June 10 (Xinhua) -- The number of German companies going
bankrupt would continue to rise for the sixth consecutive year in
1998, a record since the end of World War II, a state-backed
credit insurance company said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The Hamburg-based Hermes Kreditversicherungs-AG forecast in a
statement that the number of corporate insolvencies in Germany
would surge 5 percent to a new high of 28,800 this year.
</P>
<P>
Of all the businesses to collapse, 20,100 were western German
companies, up 4 percent over 1997, and 8,700 were in the eastern
area of the country, up 7 percent.
</P>
<P>
The services and in particular the construction sector would be
hardest hit, according to the insurance company. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
