<DOCNO> XIE19980611.0005 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zimbabwean Industrial Potential Highlighted </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, June 10 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwe has great potential as an
exporter of manufactured products despite the handicaps of its
landlocked position, a Commonwealth Secretariat official said
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Christopher Easter, Deputy Director in the Economic Affairs
Division of the Commonwealth Secretariat made the remarks while
addressing delegates at a two-day seminar on "Export
Competitiveness in Zimbabwe" in Harare.
</P>
<P>
Zimbabwe had an advantage in that it had a diverse base of
natural resources, low wages for literate labor, good physical
infrastructure and strong manufacturing capabilities, the
Zimbabwe News Agency quoted him as saying.
</P>
<P>
"These strengths have not yet been fully realized. The
country's manufactured exports are still fairly small compared
with other export-oriented economies, the slow growing,
fragmented regional market remains the main destination for
exports and many legacies of inward-orientation persist in
policies and enterprise behavior, he said.
</P>
<P>
Easter said a study to enhance export competitiveness in
Zimbabwe reviewed the competitive strengths and weaknesses at the
national and enterprise levels, relative to international
competitors in Asia, Africa and Latin America.
</P>
<P>
The study would highlight key areas for future analysis and
action as Zimbabwe moved toward re-engineering its economy,
particularly its export sector, he said.
</P>
<P>
The study suggested the establishment of a Zimbabwe
Competitive Council to oversee all issues relating to sustaining
national competitiveness, and creation of a stable and credible
macro-economic environment.
</P>
<P>
It also suggested the development of strong export promotion
policies, a targeted foreign investment promotion strategy and
the promotion of small and medium enterprise competitiveness.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
