<HEADLINE> Arafat to Hold Talks With Jordanian PM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, June 10 (Xinhua) -- Palestinian National Authority
(PNA) President Yasser Arafat and Jordanian Prime Minister
Abdul-Salam Majali are scheduled to discuss the latest
developments in the stalled Mideast peace process in Gaza
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
"Chairman Arafat just returned from Burkina Faso and he will
discuss with Majali about the latest developments concerning the
peace process and the ongoing efforts about the convening of an
Arab summit," a PNA official close to Arafat told Xinhua from
Gaza.
</P>
<P>
Upon his return, Arafat said that all efforts of peace have
failed and the contacts are still going on for convening the Arab
summit, the official noted.
</P>
<P>
Arafat also criticized the Israeli government's approval to
build 58 housing units on Mount of Olives in East Jerusalem,
saying it is a blatant violation to the signed agreements between
the two sides.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli Interior Ministry approved on Tuesday the plan
submitted by the Jerusalem Municipality to build 58 new housing
units for Jewish students on Mount of Olives, to allocate a spot
on the eastern side of the Mount of Olives for an Arab girl school,
and to build 100 housing units for Palestinians in the adjacent
A-Tur neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
The PNA and the Israeli peace movement "Peace Now" opposed
the plan.
</P>
<P>
PNA Cabinet Secretary Tayeb Abdel Rahim said on Tuesday that
the decision to build new housing units for Jewish students is
proof of the continued Israeli aggression and the intent to empty
Jerusalem of its Arab residents. 
</P>
</TEXT>
