<HEADLINE> S. Africa Recruits More Black Policemen </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, June 10 (Xinhua) -- Eighty one percent of the
1,200 constables accepted into the South African police since
last year were black, the police announced Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
South African Police Services (SAPS) management was very happy
with the racial composition of the intake, SAPS divisional
commissioner Neels Steenkamp told parliament.
</P>
<P>
However, Steenkamp complained that of all new police recruits,
only one fifth were women.
</P>
<P>
The intention was to have an equal number of men and women in
the police force, he said, adding there was still a "mental or
physical barrier" to women wanting to become police officers, and
those already in the force were mostly in administrative or
support positions.
</P>
<P>
Steenkamp said the first 300 recruits started their training
at the beginning of this month, and the rest would follow in
batches of 300 at two-month intervals.
</P>
<P>
Referring to the future of the police force in the country, he
said the size of the force would be reduced over the next five
years from its present 129,233 to 120,000 well-trained, well-paid
and well-motivated. 
</P>
</TEXT>
