<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Canada's Computer Jobs Double in Five Years </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, June 10 (Xinhua) -- Jobs for computer programers and
system analysts almost doubled in Canada from 1992 to 1997,
Statistics Canada reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
In 1997, the country had 267,000 such jobs, which was 92
percent more than that of 1992.
</P>
<P>
"The unemployment rate for computer programers in 1997 was
about 3 percent lower than any national unemployment rate since
the mid-1960s," the statistics agency said.
</P>
<P>
Factors contributing to this expanding job market include the
rapid growth of the Internet, the spread of intranets in large
organizations, as well as the growing demand for people who can
fix the so-called year 2000 problem.
</P>
<P>
Those programers with previous work experience had the best
luck finding jobs, with the number of those aged over 45 growing
by 131 percent in the five-year period, and those aged between 25
and 34 up by 66 percent.
</P>
<P>
Data shows that programers are not wealthy workaholics as they
were perceived in the past, the agency said.
</P>
<P>
They worked an average 38.8 hours a week in 1997, and the
average earnings per week stood at 843 Canadian dollars (580 U.S.
dollars), while those workers in the natural science, engineering
and mathematics group earned 877 dollars per week. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
