<DOCNO> XIE19980611.0010 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. African Opposition Parties Meet on Coop Talks  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
JOHANNESBURG, June 10 (Xinhua) -- South Africa's two
opposition parties have met to discuss possible opposition
stranglehold on power.
</P>
<P>
During a four-hour meeting in Cape Town on Tuesday night,
leaders of the biggest opposition National Party (NP), and the
Democratic Party (DP), a white-based opposition party, had "a
frank exchange of views" but they did not reach any agreement#,
South African Press Association quoted a joint statement by the
two parties as saying Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
"No conclusions were arrived at, other than that other
parties should be involved in any process," the statement said.
</P>
<P>
The NP's delegation consisted of party leader Marthinus van
Schalkwyk and three Western Cape provincial leaders, including
Premier Gerald Morkel. The DP delegation comprised party leader
Tony Leon, his deputy William Mnisi and five other senior
officials.
</P>
<P>
The meeting was a follow-up to formal talks late last year
between the parties' leadership, the report said.
</P>
<P>
With the 1999 general election around the corner, the NP had
repeatedly called on opposition parties to join forces to fight
the ruling ANC in the polls. The DP also indicated its
willingness to form an opposition alliance.
</P>
<P>
While declining to give details about the substance of the
talks, a DP delegate to the meeting said Wednesday it was routine
and part of an ongoing program of consultations with other
parties.
</P>
<P>
He said Leon had suggested a basis for cooperation among
opposition parties.
</P>
<P>
Van Schalkwyk described Monday's meeting as "very important",
the report said.
</P>
<P>
"Cooperation between like-minded opposition parties is
vital," Schalkwyk said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The NP had tabled a number of proposals, including a council
of opposition parties in which all would have equal status,
regardless of size, he said. But he emphasized that the talks
were preliminary and there had not been discussions about
cooperation with other opposition parties.
</P>
<P>
The NP's federal executive would meet in mid-June and the
NP-DP meeting would be on the agenda, van Schalkwyk said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
