<DOCNO> XIE19980611.0012 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-10 16:48 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Eritrea Seeks African Mediation to End Border </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, June 10 (Xinhua) -- Eritrea Wednesday sought the
mediation of Egypt and other African countries to end its bloody
border dispute with Ethiopia, Egypt's Middle East News Agency
reported.
</P>
<P>
"We want Egypt to play a role in this respect besides other
African countries, as Egypt has a major role within the
Organization of African Unity (OAU)," said Aboudula Mahmoud Jaber,
the political advisor of Eritrean President Issayas Aferwerki.
</P>
<P>
"Both the Eritreans and Ethiopians share good relations with
Egypt," Jaber told reporters after his meeting with Egyptian
President Hosni Mubarak here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Jaber said that basic differences between Eritrea and Ethiopia
are over borders inherited since the days of colonialism.
</P>
<P>
Ethiopia and Eritrea have argued peacefully over their border
for years, but the dispute turned violent on May 6, with each
accusing the other of incursions. Hopes that U.S.-led mediation
would prevent a deterioration were dashed last weekend as bloody
clashes had occurred.
</P>
<P>
The two countries, among the world's poorest, are at odds over
at least six areas along their common border. They were one state
until Eritrea gained independence from Ethiopia in 1993.
</P>
<P>
The meeting between Jaber and Mubarak was attended by members
of an Eritrean delegation which arrived here Tuesday night to
inform Egyptian officials of the developments on the
Eritrean-Ethiopian borders.
</P>
<P>
Eritrean Minister of Local Government Mohamud Sherifo handed
over a message from Aferwerki to Mubarak during the meeting.
</P>
<P>
The Egyptian leader has sent two messages to leaders of both
Eritrea and Ethiopia, calling for an immediate end to the
fightings and holding negotiations to resolve the border row that
centers on a 400 square kilometers rocky triangle of land along
their western border.
</P>
<P>
Heavy fighting erupted Tuesday along the Ethiopian-Eritrean
frontier as the Horn of Africa neighbors turned their armies
against each other in the latest chapter of an escalating border
dispute.
</P>
<P>
The OAU has reportedly agreed to send a high-level mediation
team to the disputed border area between Ethiopia and Eritrea for
mediation to end the confrontation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
