<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ethiopia Accused of Arming Separatists </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOGADISHU, June 10 (Xinhua) -- Somalia's three political
factions Wednesday accused Ethiopia of meddling in Somalia's
internal affairs by supplying arms to separatists.
</P>
<P>
The three factions -- the Somali National movement (SNM), the
Somali Democratic Alliance (SDA) and the United Somali Front
(USF) which originate from Somalia's Northwestern regions have
accused Ethiopia of supplying large amounts of military weapons
to Ibrahim Egal of the breakaway republic of Somaliland.
</P>
<P>
In a strong-worded statement issued in Mogadishu, the three
factions have also condemned Ethiopia for defying the resolutions
by the U.N., the Organization of African Unity (OAU) and the
regional organization of Inter-Governmental Authority for
Development (IGAD), which impose arms embargo on Somalia.
</P>
<P>
The signatories of the statement included Abdurahman Ahmed Ali
Tur, the chairman of the SNM. They have also blamed Ethiopia for
violating Somalia's unity and territorial integrity by constantly
sending its military officials to Hargeisa, capital of the
breakaway republic of Somaliland.
</P>
<P>
The three factions are allied with faction leader Hussein
Mohamed Aidid and they said Ethiopia has already given diplomatic
recognition to Egal by opening its own mission in Hargeisa while
reciprocally offering an office to the secessionist
administration of Egal in Addis Ababa to promote what they called
Ethiopia's particular military and economic interests.
</P>
<P>
The three factions also said they will no longer tolerate what
they called Ethiopia's deliberate and arrogant intransigence.
</P>
<P>
Ethiopia last year supplied weapons and ammunition to the
factions of Ali Mahdi Mohamed and the Somali Salvation Democratic
Front.
</P>
<P>
They have also made two armed insurgencies into Somalia's
border region of Gedo in their support of the Somali National
Front fighting against the Islamic fundamentalist group of
Al-Itihad Al-Islam.
</P>
<P>
Ethiopian military officials have also opened early in the
year three training camps for the Hawadle clan militiamen in the
central region of Hiran.
</P>
<P>
At least 750 former militiamen trained and supervised by
Ethiopia are currently operating in Hiran in accordance with the
Ethiopian led program which still remains unknown. 
</P>
</TEXT>
