<HEADLINE> Israel, Hezbollah to Exchange Detainees, Remains </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, June 10 (Xinhua) -- Lebanese leading anti-Israel Muslim
group Hezbollah is expected to swap on June 17 the remains of a
killed Israeli soldier for Lebanese detainees held in Israel, the
Orient radio reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The radio quoted sources of the Shiite Muslim Amal Movement
led by Lebanese Parliament Speaker Nabih Berri as saying that
Israel will free 50 Lebanese detainees from its south Lebanon
Khiam prison and return 40 remains of killed Lebanese guerillas.
</P>
<P>
In return, Hezbollah, or Party of God, will return the remains
of an Israeli soldier killed in an Israeli bungled commando raid
on the Lebanese southern coastal village of Insariyeh last
September.
</P>
<P>
The sources added that the swap is expected to be carried out
in the Feraruz crossing in south Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
The Lebanese detainees and remains of the killed guerillas
which will be returned by Israel would be mainly from Amal
movement and the Iranian-backed Hezbollah. The two groups have
been fighting Israeli troops and trying to oust them from south
Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
Israel set up a 1,200-square-kilometer so-called security zone
in south Lebanon in 1985 with the claimed aim of protecting its
northern settlements from Lebanese guerrilla cross-border attacks.
</P>
<P>
The current negotiations are under way between Israel and
Hezbollah through the International Committee of the Red Cross
and the Lebanese government. 
</P>
</TEXT>
