<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-10 17:23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iran to Cut Oil Output by 100,000 Barrels Per Day </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, June 10 (Xinhua) -- Iran Wednesday announced to cut
its oil production by 100,000 barrels per day (bpd) as of July 1,
joining the efforts of other oil exporters to boost oil prices.
</P>
<P>
The announcement was made following a meeting between Iranian
Oil Minister Bijan Namdar Zanganeh and his visiting Saudi
counterpart Ali al-Naimi, the Iranian official news agency IRNA
reported.
</P>
<P>
"Iran undertakes to trim output by 100,000 bpd as of July 1, in
addition to the 140,000 bpd cut previously agreed upon," the oil
ministry said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
Iran's decision came after Saudi Arabia, Venezuela and Mexico
reached an agreement in Amsterdam on Thursday to further cut
their oil productions.
</P>
<P>
In a swift reaction, Tehran hailed the output cuts, stating
that it supports any collective action by members of the
Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries (OPEC) to restore
the oil market and shore up the prices.
</P>
<P>
Iran, the second largest exporter in the OPEC block, has a
production quota of 3.94 million bpd according to the OPEC
decision made in November. But its actual production is much less
than the figure due to its out-of-date facilities.
</P>
<P>
Suffering a sharp fall in oil incomes during last Iranian year
(ended March 20), Iran repeatedly announced readiness to
cooperate with other OPEC countries, Saudi Arabia in particular,
to cut oil production in order to boost prices.
</P>
<P>
The Saudi oil minister arrived here on Tuesday on a trip to
lobby oil exporters to join efforts to restore oil market. He
earlier visited Kuwait, the United Arab Emirates, Qatar and Oman
to seek their support. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
