<HEADLINE> Iraq Condemns U.S., Britain for Using Depleted </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, June 10 (Xinhua) -- Iraq's ruling Baath Socialist
Party on Wednesday condemned U.S. and British troops for using
depleted uranium bombs against Iraqi troops during the 1991 Gulf
War.
</P>
<P>
A statement by the party's Foreign Relations Bureau, released
by the official Iraqi News Agency, said the use of such weapons
constituted a serious crime as their subsequent effects are not
only confined to direct injuries, but also include long-standing
contamination of soil, water and air.
</P>
<P>
It emphasized that the subsequent effects of the use of
depleted uranium bombs will affect the health of coming
generations through touching, breathing, drinking and ingestion.
</P>
<P>
The statement referred to the findings of many international
studies, which demonstrated the detrimental effects of these
internationally banned bombs and their contribution to the
increased incidence of cancers and congenital deformities among
children.
</P>
<P>
The party appealed to all forces of good will in the world to
expose the true nature of this grave crime by lodging protests
through all possible channels to international organizations, the
U.N. Human Rights Commission and the U.S. and British government.
</P>
<P>
It added that the U.S. and Britain should be held responsible
legally and humanely for committing this horrendous crime against
the people of Iraq. 
</P>
</TEXT>
