<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Deplores Russia's Delay on Start II </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 10 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright Wednesday deplored the Russian parliament's
latest refusal to approve a treaty sharply reducing nuclear
weapons.
</P>
<P>
Speaking on arms control at the Henry Stimson Center in
Washington, Albright said the decision of the Duma was a serious
setback to efforts to curb the spread of nuclear weapons around
the world. "I deeply regret that action."
</P>
<P>
Earlier Wednesday, Russia's Duma, or the parliament, decided
to postpone hearings on the START II arms reduction treaty from
next week until the fall, further delaying hopes of ratification.
</P>
<P>
Albright said she hoped the Duma would reverse itself and
recognize that nuclear testing in India and Pakistan made
approval of the Start II treaty even more vital.
</P>
<P>
The treaty was concluded in 1992 and ratified by the U.S.
Senate in 1996.
</P>
<P>
Albright reiterated the U.S. position not to proceed with
anything more than preliminary negotiations on a follow-up treaty
to make even deeper cuts until the Russian parliament acts on
Start II.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Albright urged the Senate to ratify the
Comprehensive Test Ban Treaty. The Indian and Pakistani tests
made the treaty more crucial because it would set up a monitoring
system and try to curb proliferation of nuclear weapons
technology, she added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
