<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rawlings Defends OAU Summit's Function </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OUAGADOUGOU, June 10 (Xinhua) -- Ghanaian President Jerry
Rawlings said Wednesday the OAU summit was not at all a social
gathering of African leaders but a forum for them to discuss hot
issues facing the continent.
</P>
<P>
"It allows a room for an interchange to reduce frictions and
the suspicions that exist among African countries," Rawlings told
Xinhua at the end of the three-day summit of the Organization of
African Unity (OAU) here.
</P>
<P>
"I think it has been conducted in a very competent way and the
exchange among us has been very healthy," the Ghanaian president
said.
</P>
<P>
"It has given an opportunity for us to express our feelings on
certain issues, and this is why I find the agenda for this
session is very interesting," he added.
</P>
<P>
Peace and economic development are issues of priority which
were put high on the agenda of the OAU summit, which ended with a
renewal of African leaders' commitment to building a stronger
Africa in the new millennium.
</P>
<P>
Rawlings, reported to be close friend of Nigeria's late Head
of State General Sani Abacha, also commented on the leader of the
most populous country in Africa.
</P>
<P>
Abacha reportedly died of a heart attack shortly before his
departure to attend the summit Monday morning.
</P>
<P>
Describing the late general as "a great nationalist of his
country," Rawlings gave the credit that in his time, Abacha "was
able to reduce the massive debt of Nigeria."
</P>
<P>
Although the Nigerian people are suffering from hardships at
present, they will see the fruits under Abacha's leadership,
according to him.
</P>
<P>
The Ghanaian president believed that the domestic policies and
those toward the west African sub-region made under Abacha would
be maintained.
</P>
<P>
On the current conflict between Ethiopia and Eritrea as well
as the situation in Guinea Bissau, which have become hot spots of
the continent, Rawlings said, "I don't think they are
non-containable problems."
</P>
<P>
According to him, African leaders at the summit had an
opportunity to discuss these issues and take some steps in order
to prevent the situations from escalating.
</P>
<P>
Describing the relationship between China and Ghana as "very
healthy," Rawlings said, "we intend to transfer this relationship
into as many fields of our economic and trading activities as
possible."
</P>
<P>
He said he hoped to see more exchange of visits by leaders
of the two countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
