<HEADLINE> No Merger Among Egypt's State-owned Banks: Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, June 10 (Xinhua) -- Governor of the Central Bank of
Egypt Ismail Hassan said Wednesday that there are no plans to
merge any of the four biggest public sector banks, the Middle
East News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
"Egypt has no plan in any way to amalgamate either among these
banks or with any other private or joint bank," he told
reporters. He said that statements made in this connection were
without foundation.
</P>
<P>
He referred to a statement published by the Egyptian Al Alam
Al Youm newspaper Wednesday and said such statements "served no
cause and caused confusion."
</P>
<P>
The four largest national banks, namely, the National
bank of Egypt, Misr Bank, Bank of Alexandria and National
Investment Bank, hold 70 percent of the country's commercial
assets, 60 percent of deposits and 68 percent of loans.
</P>
<P>
Hassan said public sector banks are owned by the state who has
not decided on such a step.
</P>
<P>
"If there ever was such a trend -- and this is not under
consideration at present -- this would be considered by owners of
the banks in accordance with rules and procedures provided in
current laws," he said.
</P>
<P>
The governor of the central bank said he was aware that
amalgamations are "a feature of the age" in the banking sector and
industrial companies, but he added such procedures take place at
the decision of shareholders with the right timing and the
right circumstances.
</P>
<P>
The Egyptian People's Assembly approved in principle Monday a
draft bill regulating contribution of the private sector in the
capital of public sector banks.
</P>
<P>
The bill says that the private sector may contribute to the
shares of the capital of banks wholly owned by the state. It gives
no timetable for the government to offer the banks for sale.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
