<HEADLINE> Britain Welcomes EC Proposal to lift Beef Ban </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, June 10 (Xinhua) -- The British government Wednesday
welcomed the European Commission's proposal to lift the
two-year-old global ban on British beef exports.
</P>
<P>
The commission, the executive branch of the European Union
(EU), announced early Wednesday that it had proposed lifting all
the restrictions on British beef exports.
</P>
<P>
However, the proposal is yet to be discussed by EU veterinary
experts and is expected to pass on to EU agriculture ministers for
a final decision.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on this proposal, British Agriculture Minister Jack
Cunningham was quoted by BBC television as saying, "It is very
good news, but it is not the end of the story."
</P>
<P>
"Clearly we shall be doing everything we can to minimize the
time between this announcement and the final agreement for beef to
flow again into international markets," Cunningham said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, President of the British National Farmers Union Ben
Gill said, "We've now turned the corner and we are in the home
straight. The momentum must not be lost."
</P>
<P>
The EU imposed the worldwide ban on all British beef exports in
March 1996 when the British government admitted possible links
between mad cow disease and its human equivalent Creutzfeldt-Jakob
Disease.
</P>
<P>
Last month, EU ministers decided to lift the beef products
export ban on Britain's Northern Ireland region, where a computer
database can track cattle movements. 
</P>
</TEXT>
