<HEADLINE> Heated Debate Continues In Israel Over Redeployment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, June 10 (Xinhua) -- The heated debate among Israel's
ruling coalition continued Wednesday on the long-overdue troop
redeployment in the West Bank, dimming the hope for a quick
breakthrough over the issue.
</P>
<P>
The far rightist coalition lawmakers renewed their warning that
they would leave the government if Prime Minister Benjamin
Netanyahu goes ahead with his plan to carry out a major
redeployment.
</P>
<P>
To show the seriousness of their warning, 11 members of the
Land of Israel Front, the far-rightist parliamentary faction that
opposes any land handover to the Palestinians, held a meeting with
prominent religious figures, Rabbi Abraham Shapira and Mordechai
Eliahu, religious mentors of the major coalition party National
Religious Party (NRP).
</P>
<P>
They said they were drafting a religious ruling which would
obligate the NRP lawmakers to topple the government if Netanyahu
gives up more land of the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
The NRP, a religious party that still embraces the ideology of
Greater Israel which believes Israel must retain control over the
land between the Mediterranean Sea and the Jordan River, has
repeatedly threatened to oust Netanyahu if he carries out a
redeployment of exceeding 9 percent.
</P>
<P>
It seemed that amid reports that Netanyahu is close to a
U.S.-brokered deal on a 13 percent redeployment, the
far-rightwingers felt an urge to deter the prime minister from
doing so.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the centrist coalition party The Third Way came out
to prod Netanyahu to move forward on the redeployment issue. The
party warned that it would also bring down the government, if no
agreement will be reached on the second redeployment.
</P>
<P>
Party member Yehuda Harel described his Tuesday meeting with
Netanyahu as the "toughest" one, but said he was not sure the
prime minister was trying to wrap up the second redeployment. If
there was no agreement on the issue, The Third Way would try to
topple the government and go to early elections, he said.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, the opposition party Meretz also presented a
no-confidence motion to the Knesset (Parliament) over the
government's indecision on the redeployment, saying the current
negotiations were "nothing but a bluff."
</P>
<P>
Despite the continued negotiations and contacts through the
U.S. mediation, the prospect for a quick breakthrough faded due to
the strong opposition that Netanyahu is facing within his
government. Netanyahu denied earlier this week the reports that he
was on the verge of a deal with the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
He once again toughened his tone Wednesday, saying that the
real peace with the Palestinians must be based on Israeli security
and the Palestinian compliance with existing agreements.
</P>
<P>
Speaking in Jerusalem at a meeting of Haifa University's Board
of Governors, he reiterated that Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat
must expunge clauses in the Palestinian Covenant calling for
Israel's destruction.
</P>
<P>
"How can Israel be expected to make further concessions to the
Palestinian Authority, when it refuses to say that the covenant
calling for Israel's destruction has been rescinded?" he asked.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
