<HEADLINE> U.N. Chief Expresses Concern Over Increased Tension </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, June 10 (Xinhua) -- U.N. Secretary-General Kofi
Annan Wednesday expressed his serious concern over the increased
tension in Gali district of Abkhazia, Georgia.
</P>
<P>
The tension in this area appears to have persisted in spite of
the signing on May 25, 1998 of the Protocol on a Cease-Fire and
Withdrawal of Armed Formations.
</P>
<P>
In a statement, the U.N. chief appealed urgently to the
government of Georgia and the Abkhaz authorities to settle their
dispute at the negotiating table and not through armed
confrontation, which would only lead to further unnecessary human
suffering and additional loss of life.
</P>
<P>
Annan expressed the hope that a meeting between the Georgian
president and the Abkhaz leader will take place soon and that it
will contribute to defusing the situation on the ground.
</P>
<P>
He said he has instructed his special representative to pursue
vigorously his contacts with both sides with a view to resuming
the Geneva process. 
