<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Retail Sales Increase Strongly in May </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 11 (Xinhua) -- Thanks to the strong spending
on cars and trucks, the U.S. retail sales increased 0.9 percent in
May, marking the seventh consecutive monthly growth, the Commerce
Department reported here Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The increase, to a seasonally adjusted 224.6 billion U.S.
dollars, was larger than predicted by some economists and followed
a 0.7 percent gain in April, revised up from an earlier estimate
of 0.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
May's gain was the largest since February, when unseasonably
mild winter weather helped keep Americans shopping. But the
persistence of strong buying demand into the April-June quarter
implies economic growth may not drop all that much from the
robust 4.8 percent annual rate reached during the first quarter.
</P>
<P>
In May, auto sales surged 2.4 percent, hitting 1.51 million
units of cars and trucks, the best performance in 12 years.
</P>
<P>
General merchandise stores, including department stores, also
reported strong sales. They rose 0.6 percent last month after an
even-better 0.9 percent gain in April.
</P>
<P>
Sales jumped 1.5 percent at furniture and home appliance
stores, the best in four months, and 0.7 percent at gas stations.
They inched 0.2 percent higher at food stores.
</P>
<P>
However, sales fell 0.3 percent at drug stores, 0.1 percent at
building supply and hardware stores and 0.1 percent at restaurants
and bars. Receipts were unchanged at apparel and specialty shops.
</P>
<P>
In another separate report released Thursday, the Labor
Department said the number of first-time claims for unemployment
insurance dropped by a seasonally adjusted 23,000 to 315,000 last
week. A less-volatile four-week moving average of claims rose by
2,250 to 319,000, a low number but nevertheless the highest since
late January. 
</P>
</TEXT>
