<HEADLINE> Top Legislature Urges Law Enforcement Inspectors to Be Honest </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 11 (Xinhua) -- China's top legislature today
urged its law inspection inspectors to be honest in performing their
duties.
</P>
<P>
An inspection team for law enforcement is to leave for Shandong
Province tomorrow, checking on the observance of the Law on Marine
Environmental Protection. The series of law inspections,
which started in mid-May, are the first of their kind initiated by
the Standing Committee of the Ninth National People's Congress
(NPC).
</P>
<P>
Two other teams are to go to coastal areas of Liaoning
Province and the island province of Hainan.
</P>
<P>
The NPC Standing Committee stressed that inspection teams must
not participate in banquets or accept any gifts from
localities. All the members must oppose extravagance and waste.
</P>
<P>
Furthermore, they should report both their positive and
negative findings to the country's highest legislature, which has
unprecedentedly organized seven law-enforcement inspections this
year.
</P>
<P>
Since 1993, the NPC Standing Committee has decided that it
must strengthen the checking and supervision of laws for the overall
development of the country, especially in the market economy.
</P>
<P>
In the past five years, the Standing Committee has organized 23
inspection teams, checking 21 laws, decisions and
resolutions.
</P>
<P>
This year the Standing Committee will inspect the observance of
the Agriculture Law, Law on Water and Soil Conservation, Law on
Administration of Taxation, Law on Marine Environmental
Protection, Law on Application of Scientific and Technological
Findings and two others.
</P>
<P>
In accordance with the law, the inspection teams will not be
involved in the settlement of problems but urge
governmental departments to effectively implement the laws.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980611.0038 </DOCNO>
