<HEADLINE> Indonesian Military Asked to Reveal Truth on Riots </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, June 11 (Xinhua) -- Indonesian President B. J. Habibie
here Thursday asked the Armed Forces (ABRI) to reveal truth about
the mastermind of riots in Jakarta more than three weeks ago,
according to Antara News Agency.
</P>
<P>
Habibie asked the military to make the revelation during a
meeting with high-ranking officers of the ABRI, including Defense
Minister and ABRI commander Gen. Wiranto.
</P>
<P>
The president asked the military to reveal if there was an
organized group that provoked people to damage, loot and burn
vehicles and stores during the widespread rioting that rocked
Jakarta between May 13 and 15.
</P>
<P>
More than 5,000 shops and houses were burned and looted and
more than 1,200 people killed in the riots.
</P>
<P>
The riots had eventually forced former President Soeharto to
step down and install Habibie as the country's third president.
</P>
<P>
During the meeting, Habibie stressed that the country and the
international community are still sensitive about the riots, the
way they were handled and the death toll, with respect to the
observance of human rights.
</P>
<P>
Human rights, unlike in the past, can no longer be ignored as
they have become a measurement of a country's development, Habibie
said.
</P>
<P>
He thus expressed hope that the armed forces would follow the
U.N. conventions that the government has pledged to ratify in
stages.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, a social organization working for harmonious
inter-ethnic relations on Wednesday called on the ABRI to issue a
guarantee for the safety of all non-indigenous Indonesians.
</P>
<P>
The organization also proposed to Habibie that the government
issue an official statement condemning all the violations of human
rights that occurred during the riots.
</P>
<P>
Indonesian TV station Thursday reported that Habibie will sign
a decree next week, abolishing the use of "non-indigenous" to
describe other ethnic groups in the country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
