<HEADLINE> Indian MPs Say 2,000 Killed in Cyclonic Storm </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, June 11 (Xinhua) -- Members in the Lower House of
the Indian Parliament said Thursday that some 2,000 people were
killed and 50,000 others were missing in the deadly cyclonic storm
that lashed the west coast of India Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Bhavnaben Dave from the ruling Bharatiya Janata Party (BJP)
told the house that the severe storm caused massive devastation in
many parts of Gujarat though the state government had taken
elaborate precautions.
</P>
<P>
Official figures put the death toll at 565 including nine in
neighboring Rajasthan till Thursday morning as army and civil
authorities fought adverse conditions to rescue survivors and
provide relief to them.
</P>
<P>
Reports from the hit areas said 151 bodies have been identified
so far and with recovery of more bodies from the rubbles of
flattened houses and uprooted trees and electric poles along the
coastal areas, the toll would most likely further go up.
</P>
<P>
Many of the deaths and those missing are salt workers who were
washed away into the sea by the tidal waves rising from the Gulf
of Kutch and could only be discovered later.
</P>
<P>
The cyclone, which entered the coastal city of Porbandar,
Gujarat State, around 10:30 a.m. Tuesday and weakened Wednesday
morning, left an unprecedented trail of destruction and paralyzed
life in the hit areas.
</P>
<P>
Civil authorities, assisted by the army and the air force,
began a massive relief and rescue operation shortly after the
storm, but widespread heavy rains that followed in the devastated
areas have made the relief work more difficult.
</P>
<P>
Thousands of houses were damaged and road and communication
links disrupted and cities like Jamnagar, Porbandar, Gandhidham,
Bhuj and Khambhaliya in the state were in total darkness.
</P>
<P>
Initial estimates said colossal damage to property is worth
around 12 billion rupees, or 300 million U.S. dollars in Kutch and
Saurashtra areas.
</P>
<P>
Indian Prime Minister Atal Bihari Vajpayee appealed Wednesday
night to Indians and those of Indian origin living abroad to make
generous contributions to the relief work in the devastated areas.
</P>
<P>
The Indian government said it would issue a statement on the
disaster later Thursday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
