<HEADLINE> EU, China Sign Cooperation Projects </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, June 11 (Xinhua) -- The European Union and China
signed several cooperation projects Thursday to promote the
economy in China's Tibetan Autonomous Region.
</P>
<P>
The projects, worth 84 million ECU (92.4 million U.S. dollars),
include an integrated rural development project to enhance the
agricultural self-sufficiency of ethnic Tibetan people by
improving food production through better irrigation.
</P>
<P>
The long-term protection of grazing land and the development of
training facilities for the local population are also contained in
the projects.
</P>
<P>
The projects were signed by European Commission Vice-President
Sir Leon Brittan and visiting Chinese Minister of Foreign Trade
and Economic Cooperation Shi Guangshen.
</P>
<P>
Shi and Brittan also signed a memorandum of understanding,
through which the 15-nation union is expected to help China build
a robust financial sector in the wake of the Asian financial
crisis.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese minister came here for the annual EU-China Joint
Committee meeting, which focused on a wide range of bilateral
trade issues, including the problems facing European companies
investing in China, the export of dual-use products, and the fight
against Intellectual Property piracy.
</P>
<P>
Shi also held talks with his EU counterparts on China's
accession to the World Trade Organization.
</P>
<P>
In an earlier move, the EU removed China and Russia from its
list of non-market economy countries so as to give the two
countries better trading conditions. 
</P>
</TEXT>
