<HEADLINE> Australian Stocks Close at Five-Month Low </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, June 11 (Xinhua) -- The Australian sharemarket was
dragged down Thursday by slumps on key Asian equity markets, a low
Australian dollar and concerns about the direction of interest
rates in the nation.
</P>
<P>
The All Ordinaries Index ended down 34.2 points at a five-month
low of 2558.7, although it was 15.2 points above its low for the
day after some light buying emerged in afternoon trading.
</P>
<P>
"It was a pretty negative day for sentiment all round," said
Rob Black, an institutional dealer.
</P>
<P>
"I think there is still Asian concern. With our market, it is
more the case of there not being any buying around," he said.
</P>
<P>
The Nikkei index dropped as foreign companies moved to lighten
their equity exposure to the fragile Japanese economy while the
Hong Kong market worsened on concerns about Asian currencies and
selling of interest rate-sensitive stocks, the Australian
Associated Press reported.
</P>
<P>
That led to a further deterioration of confidence in an
Australian market already damaged this week by a drop in the value
of the Australian dollar and speculation about an official
interest rate hike.
</P>
<P>
Thursday's negativity was not restricted to currency-exposed
stocks.
</P>
<P>
Global media giant News Corp. fell after a strong run-up this
week arising from its large proportion of foreign currency
revenues. Its ordinary shares dropped 35 cents to 9.79 Australian
dollars while its preferred stock fell 28 cents to 8.54 Australian
dollars.
</P>
<P>
Financial stocks fared poorly as the market saw tangible
evidence of the arrival of a higher interest rate environment as
leading ANZ and St George banks moved to lift some fixed home loan
rates.
</P>
<P>
ANZ lost only 5 cents to 10.62 Australian dollars while St
George dropped 6 cents to 10.02 Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
Of other major banks, National Australia fell 29.8 cents to
21.005 Australian dollars, Westpac bank lost 12 cents to 9.48
Australian dollars, Commonwealth suffered a 33-cent drop to 17.4
Australian dollars and Colonial slumped 15 cents to 4.53
Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
The All Industrials Index weakened 63.4 points to 4437.6 while
the All Resources was 10 points down at 1051.2.
</P>
<P>
Australia's leading company BHP lost 9 cents to 13.35
Australian dollars after announcing an understanding to sell Timor
Sea petroleum assets.
</P>
<P>
Global miner Rio Tinto was 15 cents down at 19.5 Australian
dollars.
</P>
<P>
The gold index was 0.9 points down at 1125.2 as the bullion
price rose 4.1 U.S. dollars per ounce to 294.2 U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Turnover Thursday was 360.7 million shares worth 684.4 million
U.S. dollars. Falls of 819 outnumbered rises of 423. 
</P>
</TEXT>
