<HEADLINE> Australian Dollar Climbs Through 59 U.S. Cent Level </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, June 11 (Xinhua) -- The Australian dollar climbed
back above the key psychological level of 59 U.S. cents Thursday
but experts warned that it could head lower again Friday.
</P>
<P>
The local currency was able to briefly catch its breath
Thursday as the onslaught from offshore markets eased.
</P>
<P>
However, foreign exchange dealers said that as soon as market
participants squared their books the Australian dollar would
resume its test of the downside.
</P>
<P>
At the close in Sydney the currency was trading at 59.18 U.S.
cents from 58.32 U.S. cents at Wednesday's close.
</P>
<P>
"Overall I think it is just short squeezing at the moment and
once the market is out of its short positions the dollar will
probably have another test on the downside," said John Reedyk,
foreign exchange sales manager with the Australian and New Zealand
Banking Group.
</P>
<P>
"There has been little interest today from offshore markets,
the onshore market was still a bit short from yesterday so that is
why we've seen a short squeeze this afternoon," Reedyk said.
</P>
<P>
Earlier Thursday a dealer from the Commonwealth Bank of
Australia warned that as soon as the Japanese yen weakened against
the U.S. dollar the Australian dollar would follow suit.
</P>
<P>
The Australian dollar was also buying 83.88 Japanese yen from
82.35 yen at Wednesday night's close.
</P>
<P>
It was trading at 1.0636 German marks from 1.0385 marks, at
0.3633 British pounds from 0.3559 and 1.1792 New Zealand dollars
from 1.1788.  
</P>
