<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Albright Urges Enhanced Sino-U.S. Cooperation (Part I) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 11 (Xinhua) -- The United States hopes the
forthcoming June Sino-U.S summit will advance the two countries'
relationship in ways that serve the American and Chinese peoples,
says U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine K. Albright.
</P>
<P>
U.S. President Bill Clinton is scheduled to make a reciprocal
visit to China in late June following Chinese President Jiang
Zemin's trip to the United States last fall.
</P>
<P>
"Our main concern at the June summit will be to advance our
relationship in ways that serve the American and Chinese
people. We want to deepen our dialogue on global, regional and
bilateral issues of common concern, including non-proliferation,
human rights and trade, as well as our respective policies related
to development and conservation of energy and protection of the
environment," Albright said.
</P>
<P>
"Our aim is to work to close the gaps where we have differences
and work together to meet international challenges and promote
peace and prosperity in the world," said Albright in response to
written questions by "Outlook" weekly. The interview is published
in the June 15 issue of the magazine affiliated with Xinhua.
</P>
<P>
Albright said since the October summit, significant progress
has been made in the areas the two presidents discussed, citing
the following examples:
</P>
<P>
During her trip to China in April, Albright and Chinese Foreign
Minister Tang Jiaxuan signed an agreement establishing a hot line
between Washington and Beijing; on March 19, the United States
implemented its agreement with China on the Peaceful Uses of
Nuclear Energy; in December, U.S. Defense Secretary William Cohen
and his Chinese counterpart Chi Haotian signed the Military
Maritime Cooperation Agreement establishing procedures for the two
navies to follow; and more recently, the inaugural meeting of the
Joint Liaison Group on Law Enforcement was held in Washington.
</P>
<P>
"We've also strengthened our strategic dialogue and held
military exchanges," the secretary of state said. "In short, we
have made significant progress in the short time since the October
summit. The United States hopes to build on these accomplishments
during President Clinton's trip to China."
</P>
<P>
Speaking of U.S. policy toward China, Albright said: "Our
strategy of 'engagement' toward China is based on the premise that
a sound and stable relationship between our two countries serves
the fundamental interests of the American and Chinese peoples."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980611.0045 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Albright Urges Enhanced Sino-U.S. Cooperation  (Part II) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
"Although we have areas of disagreement, we have significant
common interests and the strong will on both sides to meet
challenges cooperatively," she said.
</P>
<P>
"In areas where we have differences we do not have a policy of
so-called 'containment.' We approach these differences, such as on
human rights, with mutual respect, candor, and a determination to
achieve real progress," she said.
</P>
<P>
"The best thing we can do to maintain positive momentum in our
relations is to continue to show to our two publics that improved
relations produce positive results for both countries," she said.
</P>
<P>
"Our trade imbalance with China is an indication of continuing
barriers to free trade," according to Albright. "We hope that
China will take steps to improve the access of foreign companies
to its markets. This would benefit the Chinese and American people
and help to bring China closer in line with international
standards."
</P>
<P>
On Taiwan, Albright said the United States maintains a firm
"one China" policy based on the three U.S.-PRC (The People's
Republic of China) joint communiques and the U.S. law. "We
maintain unofficial relations with the people in Taiwan. Because
we believe that cross-Strait communication and exchanges help
promote peace and stability in the region. We have encouraged both
the PRC and Taiwan to resume their cross-Strait dialogue," she
said.
</P>
<P>
On WTO and MFN, President Clinton supports the renewal of
China's most favored nation tariff status, Albright said. The
United States is also working actively with the Chinese government
to achieve China's entry into the World Trade Organization on
commercially viable terms.
</P>
<P>
One of the primary goals of President Clinton's trip to China will
be to increase mutual understanding between the two peoples, Albright
said.
</P>
<P>
The president hopes to be able to show contemporary China to
the American people to help outsiders see its complexity and
diversity. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
