<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippines Issues New Rule on DOSRI Loans </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, June 11 (Xinhua) -- The Central Bank of the Philippines
on Thursday approved a new ruling to strengthen controls over
banks' directors, officers, stockholders and other related
interest (DOSRI) loans.
</P>
<P>
The new ruling, approved by the central bank's decision-making
body, the Monetary Board, requires DOSRI loan borrowers to waive
their secrecy of deposits in their banks and other banks before
they are allowed to get any loan.
</P>
<P>
Central Bank Governor Gabriel Singson told reporters that the
new ruling is part of the central bank's crackdown on DOSRI
violations which have been cited as the cause in a couple of bank
failures.
</P>
<P>
"It is one important reform to tighten up on DOSRI rules,"
Singson said.
</P>
<P>
Under the existing DOSRI rules, a DOSRI loan borrower can only
borrow up to 15 percent of the total loan portfolio of a bank.
</P>
<P>
But DOSRI violations are rampant because borrowers are able to
use dummy individuals or corporations.
</P>
<P>
By forcing DOSRI borrowers to waive their right to secrecy of
their deposits, the central bank could better detect if the
borrowers are legitimate and capable of repaying their loans.
</P>
<P>
DOSRI violations can lead to the fall of a bank since the DOSRI
borrowers are basically robbing their own institutions, Singson
said.
</P>
<P>
This was most glaring in the case of Orient Bank wherein the
DOSRI loans reached up to 6.1 billion pesos (156 million U.S.
dollars) or more compared to the bank's total assets of only 8.2
billion pesos (210 million dollars), he said.
</P>
<P>
Orient Bank declared a bank holiday in February this year due
to a shortage of cash caused by the DOSRI violations. Most of the
bank's DOSRI loans are non-performing. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980611.0050 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Laos Takes Measures to Deal With Currency Fluctuation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, June 11 (Xinhua) -- The Lao government has been taking
emergency measures to deal with sharp currency fluctuations, a
report reaching here said on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with local media, the Bank of Laos Governor
Cheuang Sombounekhanh said the fluctuation in the currency
exchange, which started on May 18, plunged the value of Laos'
currency, the kip, by 16-20 percent.
</P>
<P>
He said the fluctuation has devalued the kip and made the
prices of market goods sky rocket, affecting the lives of the
people.
</P>
<P>
To deal with the situation, the Bank of Laos is considering
measures to normalize the situation, such as raising interest
rates for deposits from 19 percent to 22 percent and selling bonds
to mobilize funds, Cheuang said.
</P>
<P>
The bank will also consolidate the management of gold and other
jewellery shops, establish state-private joint venture currency
exchange shops, and possibly set up an inter-bank monetary
exchange.
</P>
<P>
Cheuang said the main reason for the financial turbulence was
brought on by speculating opportunists trying to take advantage of
the difficult economic times during the financial crisis in
Southeast Asia.
</P>
<P>
Cheuang also attributed some of the turbulence in the currency
exchange to the release of two new bank notes, the 2,000 and 5,000
kip notes.
</P>
<P>
He said between January and April this year, the kip lost 55
percent of its value, a devaluation rate similar to other
Southeast Asian countries.
</P>
<P>
Laos cannot avoid the influences of the financial crisis in the
region because of close trade relationships, the governor said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
