<HEADLINE> Australian Banks Boost Rates as Dollar Falls </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, June 11 (Xinhua) -- Three of Australian large banks
including the ANZ Thursday handed the federal government a
pre-election headache, lifting fixed home loan interest rates in
the wake of the plunging Australian dollar.
</P>
<P>
And in another psychological blow for the Howard government,
figures released by the Australian Bureau of Statistics showed
Australia's unemployment rate crept above the 8-percent mark in
May.
</P>
<P>
As the Aussie dollar clawed its way above 59 U.S. cents
Thursday, the ANZ, Bank S A and St George Bank announced increases
in their fixed-term home loan interest rates.
</P>
<P>
Non-bank lender RAMS also said it would raise its two home loan
fixed interest rates, but the central bank, the Reserve Bank of
Australia, held its nerve on official cash rates.
</P>
<P>
The lenders' announcements came after Treasurer Peter Costello
Wednesday urged against any movement on home loan rates, saying
there was no case to do so because official cash rates had not
budged.
</P>
<P>
Before the local markets opened Thursday Costello again moved
to talk up the economy and rejected any talk of a recession.
</P>
<P>
The treasurer said he is ready for an election "as from now"
and that the state of the economy would be a factor in the timing.
"You would obviously take into account the state of the Australian
economy."
</P>
<P>
Hours later the Australian Bureau of Statistics revealed a fall
in employment in May and a rising unemployment rate -- once again
hovering above 8 percent.
</P>
<P>
The jobless rate rose by 0.2 percent for the month to a
seasonally adjusted 8.1 percent while employment fell by 4,700,
the bureau said.
</P>
<P>
Employment Minister David Kemp said he expected job growth to
continue and the unemployment rate to fall over the coming months
despite the Asian crisis and economists' predictions of a lag
effect on jobs.
</P>
<P>
Both Kemp and Finance Minister John Fahey refused to speculate
on the movement in the Australian dollar and the possibility of a
rise in interest rates.
</P>
<P>
Prime Minister John Howard urged people not to be discouraged
by the fall of the Australian dollar and the Asian economic
crisis.
</P>
<P>
"Don't be discouraged by people running around saying there's a
bit of turmoil, a bit of uncertainty and therefore taxation reform
should be put on the shelf," Howard told the 500 Club in Perth.
</P>
</TEXT>
