<HEADLINE> Bangladesh Budget Presented to Parliament </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, June 11 (Xinhua) -- Bangladeshi Finance Minister Shah
A.M.S. Kibria on Thursday placed before the Jatiya Sangsad, the
country's parliament, the government budget for the 1998-99 fiscal
year beginning July 1, 1998.
</P>
<P>
The minister announced a 207.76 billion taka (about 4.52
billion U.S. dollars) revenue budget against a proposed
expenditure of 159.37 billion taka (about 3.46 billion dollars),
leaving a surplus of 48.39 billion taka (about 1.05 billion
dollars).
</P>
<P>
The revenue surplus of the coming fiscal would go toward
financing the Annual Development Program of 136 billion taka
(about 2.96 billion dollars), the minister said.
</P>
<P>
The proposed outlay for the revenue for the coming fiscal year
was 10.6 percent higher than the revised revenue of 187.77 billion
taka (about 4.08 billion dollars) of the current fiscal, with the
expenditure 9.9 percent higher than the revised budget of the
1997-98 fiscal.
</P>
<P>
The revenue receipts for the coming fiscal have been estimated
at 19.99 billion taka (about 435 million dollars) higher than the
revised revenue receipts of the current financial year of 187.77
billion taka (about 4.08 billion dollars) which shows a decrease
of 8.47 billion taka (about 184 million dollars) over the original
target.
</P>
<P>
The new budget would be up for adoption by the parliament by
June 30, on which the current fiscal year ends. Besides the
budget, the session may also consider some other bills, such as
the Code of Civil Procedure Amendment Bill, before it ends on July
10.
</P>
<P>
Members of parliament from the major opposition Bangladesh
Nationalist Party and the Jammat-e-Islami were absent from
Thursday's session of parliament. 
</P>
</TEXT>
