<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippine Central Bank Pushes for New Banking Law </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, June 11 (Xinhua) -- The Central Bank of the Philippines
is pushing for a piece of legislation that would immediately put
banks declaring a bank holiday under the government's supervision
to protect the interests of depositors.
</P>
<P>
Central Bank Deputy Governor Alberto Reyes told reporters
Thursday that the proposed legislation is part of a whole package
of legislative reforms the central bank is drawing up for the
entire banking system.
</P>
<P>
Under this proposal, Reyes said, a bank declaring a bank
holiday will be immediately put under the supervision of the
Philippine Deposit Insurance Corporation (PDIC).
</P>
<P>
This will make the rehabilitation of the bank easier and enable
the PDIC to immediately pay off insured depositors when the bank
is finally closed, he said.
</P>
<P>
At present, a bank can declare a bank holiday almost
indefinitely without being put under PDIC supervision until it is
ordered closed by the central bank.
</P>
<P>
This has been the case with Orient Bank which has been under a
bank holiday since February this year. There is still no end in
sight as to whether it will be rehabilitated or closed and
liquidated for good.
</P>
<P>
The PDIC, under present rules, only takes over a bank once the
central bank declares it insolvent and orders its closure.
</P>
<P>
The central bank is preparing a package of legislative reforms
for the banking system as part of the continuing effort to
strengthen the banking system which has already felt the bite of
the protracted Asian financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
Besides Orient Bank, two other small banks have been ordered by
the central bank to shut down this year due to serious cash-flow
problems. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
