<HEADLINE> NATO Considering Military Intervention in Kosovo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, June 11 (Xinhua) -- NATO defense ministers expressed
their preparedness on Thursday to intervene militarily "within
days" if Belgrade does not stop its use of force against civilians
in the Serbian province of Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
A North Atlantic Treaty Organization (NATO) official told
reporters on Thursday that the ministers were prepared to make a
decision regarding military intervention after further
consultation and discussion.
</P>
<P>
A timetable would be set for Belgrade to settle the Kosovo
crisis peacefully, or the Western military alliance would step
forward with its own action, the official said.
</P>
<P>
"Days rather than weeks is the timetable because there are
lessons to be learned from Bosnia," British Defense Secretary
George Robertson said.
</P>
<P>
He also said that patience was running out among the allies and
that Belgrade needs to get the message that NATO means business
and that military intervention could start within days unless
Belgrade stops its offensive against Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
NATO defense ministers are meeting in Brussels to discuss and
decide what action the alliance could take in helping solve the
Kosovo crisis.
</P>
<P>
Klaus Naumann, chairman of NATO's Military Committee, said
earlier that air strikes could be called to force Belgrade to stop
its indiscriminate use of force against civilians in its Serbian
province of Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
The Military Committee is the highest military authority within
the 16-nation alliance.
</P>
<P>
The foreign ministers of the 15-nation European Union decided
Monday to enact bans on all new European investment in Serbia and
freeze Belgrade's state-held funds in EU countries.
</P>
<P>
An arms embargo and a ban on the delivery of police equipment
to Serbia are already in force. 
</P>
</TEXT>
