<HEADLINE> Agencies Ask for Helicopters for Afghan Quake Relief </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, June 11 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations and the
International Committee of the Red Cross Thursday issued a second
urgent appeal for helicopters to aid victims of an Afghanistan
earthquake.
</P>
<P>
The appeal was made as the response to an earlier appeal was
totally insufficient, according to the two organizations.
</P>
<P>
Both organizations, as well as several donor governments, have
been battling for more than a week now to bring additional
helicopters in to deliver assistance to the victims of the May
30th earthquake in northern Afghanistan, said a press release by
the Office of the U.N. Resident/Humanitarian Coordinator for
Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
So far, despite making agreements for 10 more helicopters, none
has appeared, it said.
</P>
<P>
"This is unbelievably frustrating. In fact, it's scandalous
given that so many lives are at stake," Witschi-Cestari, U.N.
Coordinator for Afghanistan, was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
"Deals have been agreed, contracts made, and still, 11 days
after the earthquake, only a tiny fleet of helicopters is
operating. This is slowing down the whole relief operation and
preventing us from delivering help to people in desperate need of
clean water, food and shelter," he said.
</P>
<P>
"We desperately need the extra helicopters," he said. "The
donors are coming forward with money to pay for them. We have
supplies in Afghanistan to deliver. We call on governments and
companies in the region to offer us helicopters. Without them, we
can only deliver a fraction of what is needed."
</P>
<P>
An earthquake measuring 7.1 on the Richter scale rocked
Afghanistan's northern province of Badkhshan and Takhar late last
month, killing more than 3,000 people. 
</P>
