<HEADLINE> Major News Items in Leading U.S. Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 11 (Xinhua) -- The following are major news
items in leading U.S. newspapers on Thursday:
</P>
<P>
The Washington Post:
</P>
<P>
-- The House of Representatives voted to rewrite the nation's
bankruptcy laws, approving a plan that would make it harder for
cash-strapped individuals to wipe out their debts.
</P>
<P>
-- Secretary of State Madeleine Albright dismissed as
"dangerous nonsense" the criticism of international arms control
agreements by conservatives in Congress and defense hawks who
challenge the relevance of the Comprehensive Test Ban Treaty.
</P>
<P>
The New York Times:
</P>
<P>
-- The International Monetary Fund requires the Russian
government to slash its budget deficit and overhaul its tax
system if it wants to qualify for billions of dollars in
additional loans.
</P>
<P>
-- Scientists have broken the genetic code of the
tuberculosis bacterium, a germ that kills more people in the
world than any other infectious agent. The advance could open
new approaches for developing drugs and vaccines against the
microbe.
</P>
<P>
The Wall Street Journal:
</P>
<P>
-- The United States plans to conduct with its NATO allies a
large-scale air-raid exercise in Albania or Macedonia, hoping
that a symbolic show of force may persuade Yugoslavia to halt
Serbian attacks in Kosovo against ethnic Albanians.
</P>
<P>
-- Asian stocks sank amid fears the yen's weakness will hurt
the region's currencies. Hong Kong stocks fell 4.9 percent to
their lowest close in more than three years. 
</P>
