<HEADLINE> No-Confidence Motion Against Japanese PM Submitted </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, June 11 (Xinhua) -- Three Japanese opposition parties
Thursday submitted a no-confidence motion against Prime Minister
Ryutaro Hashimoto's cabinet over its poor handling of the battered
economy.
</P>
<P>
The motion was sent to congress by leaders of the opposition
Democratic Party of Japan (DPJ), the Liberal Party (LP) and the
Japanese Communist Party (JCP), Kyodo News reported.
</P>
<P>
Hashimoto's cabinet should take responsibility for its
"deflationary" policy partly brought about by last year's fiscal
austerity law, DPJ head Naoto Kan said.
</P>
<P>
A law on fiscal structure reform, which was enacted last
November, demanded the government reduce the combined deficit
of central and local governments below three percent of gross
domestic products.
</P>
<P>
The leader also criticized the government for wavering on
policy changes, delayed response to the bad loan problem and a
lack of political ethics.
</P>
<P>
The motion, however, is doomed to be killed at Friday's plenary
session of the lower house, which is controlled by the ruling
Liberal Democratic Party (LDP) headed by Hashimoto.
</P>
<P>
Members of the LDP's one-time non-cabinet ally, the Social
Democratic Party (SDP), and the New Party Sakigake, an ally of the
LDP, are expected to disapprove the motion.
</P>
<P>
The Japanese economy, once the second largest in the world, has
ground to a standstill since the early 1990s.
</P>
<P>
Despite an April stimulus spending package of a record 16
trillion yen (123 billion dollars), the Japanese currency slid
below the 141-yen level Tuesday for the first time in seven years.
</P>
<P>
Japan's fiscal deficit, which currently equals seven percent of
the GDP, is expected to reach 529 trillion yen by March 1999.
</P>
</TEXT>
