<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rwanda to Get $30m for Debt Servicing  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, June 11 (Xinhua) -- International donors have agreed
to contribute 30.2 million U.S. Dollars to support the government
Ministry of Finance said.
</P>
<P>
Referring to the recent donor's conference on Rwanda held in
Stockholm, Sweden, the director of macro-economic analysis in the
Ministry of Finance, Prosper Musafiri said, "Donors agreed to
service only the debt owed to three multilaterals: World Bank,
IFAD and ADB as the main creditors and most obligatory ones", the
Rwandan News Agency reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The government of Rwanda had requested 122.3 million
U.S.Dollars to service the external debt during that meeting.
</P>
<P>
At the end of 1997, Rwanda's total external debt is about 1.2
billion Dollars (including arrears amounting to 97.5 million
Dollars) which makes 65 percent of the country's national GDP, as
shown by the statistics presented in Stockholm.
</P>
<P>
And 81 percent of this amount (about 947 million Dollars) was
owed to multilateral creditors, while bilateral creditors were
owed 16 percent, equal to 181 million Dollars.
</P>
<P>
Suppliers credits amounted to 37.4 million Dollars which is
three percent of the total debt.
</P>
<P>
On the internal debts, Rwandan government owes about 26.3
million U.S.Dollars to the local creditors.
</P>
<P>
However, the government represented by the Minister of
Finance, Donald Kaberuka, signed an accord last year with
internal creditors on how the government will be eable to pay
debts within 15 years beginning from 1998.  
</P>
</TEXT>
