<HEADLINE> Malaysian Companies Urged to Be "Euro-Ready" </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, June 11 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia's companies have to
be "euro-ready" to take advantage of a single currency within
Europe's Economic and Monetary Union (EMU) member countries,
Citibank EMU specialist and foreign exchange sales head Stephen Li
said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
"Malaysian companies which are euro-ready stand to gain the
most from the creation of the EMU, one of the largest economic
restructurings the world has ever seen," he said in a statement
issued by Citibank.
</P>
<P>
"Even if Malaysian companies feel relatively insulated, they
will still have to make or receive the occasional euro payment
which will require that their financial systems be able to do so,"
Li said.
</P>
<P>
Based on 1997 figures, the EMU will become Malaysia's third
largest trading market behind the United States and Japan.
</P>
<P>
The EMU, scheduled to kick off on January 1, 1999, will have 11
countries as its initial members, namely Germany, Austria,
Belgium, Finland, France, Luxembourg, Ireland, Italy, Spain,
Portugal and the Netherlands.
</P>
<P>
A fixed exchange rate between the currencies of EMU member
countries and the euro will be held until the currencies cease to
exist on July 1, 2002.
</P>
<P>
"There are many business opportunities to be explored given the
vibrant economic cooperation between Europe and the Asia Pacific
region," Li added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
