<HEADLINE> Japanese Yen Blamed for Indonesian Rupiah's Weakness </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, June 11 (Xinhua) -- The Indonesian central bank has
attributed the rupiah's (the country's national currency) weak
condition in the last few days to external factors, especially the
Japanese yen's depreciation against the U.S. dollar.
</P>
<P>
In the last few days, the rupiah continued to drop against the
U.S. dollar and traded at 15,000 per dollar on Thursday, the
lowest level since January this year.
</P>
<P>
The rupiah is expected to regain strength after the
disbursement of an International Monetary Fund (IMF) loan, Bank
Indonesia Governor Syahril Sabirin said here Thursday following a
meeting with President B. J. Habibie.
</P>
<P>
The IMF is scheduled to disburse its third tranche of 1 billion
U.S. dollars in early July. Indonesia has received 4 billion
dollars from the IMF which had organized a 43 billion dollar
bailout package to Indonesia since October last year.
</P>
<P>
Local currency dealers said the fluctuation of the rupiah was
most possibly caused by the uncertain political climate in the
country, such as widespread demonstrations.
</P>
<P>
It could also be caused by the weakening of the yen which hit
140 against the greenback, they said.
</P>
<P>
The rupiah has lost more than 80 percent of its value against
the U.S. dollar since July last year when the monetary crisis
started in the Southeast Asian region. 
</P>
</TEXT>
