<HEADLINE> Army Officers Arrested for Corruption </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, June 11 (Xinhua) -- Five South Korean Army officers have
been arrested for accepting money from parents of young men who
asked for exemption from the mandatory 26-month military service
or better assignments, the Defense Ministry said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The five officers of the Military Manpower Administration
allegedly received a total of 540 million won (about 400,000
U.S. dollars) from parents of 138 soldiers for granting the
exemptions or better assignments.
</P>
<P>
The ministry said the 138 soldiers will be re-evaluated.
</P>
<P>
The scandal, the largest one in the military's history, was
brought to light amid suspicions that wealthy or influential
people, businessmen and executives of large corporations,
attempted to get military exemptions for their sons.
</P>
<P>
The ministry revealed the names of 12 fathers who bribed
officers, but didn't disclose names of those parents whose sons
received better assignments.
</P>
<P>
South Korean Defense Minister Chun Yong-taek apologized to the
public for the scandal, vowing to take measures to prevent similar
irregularities.
</P>
<P>
"I deeply apologize for these irregularities, and the Defense
Ministry will continue to push reform so that such a scandal will
not happen again," Chun said in a statement. 
</P>
</TEXT>
