<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S.Korea to Defend Use of Land Mines at U.N. Conference </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, June 11 (Xinhua) -- South Korea will demand that the use
of land mines be exempt from the category of `war-crime behavior'
when it attends a U.N. conference on the proposed establishment of an
International criminal court.
</P>
<P>
"South Korea and the United States will oppose including land
mines in the category of banned weapons," a spokesman of the
Ministry of Foreign Affairs and Trade said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Some 100 nations will discuss the creation of the international
court, which will handle exclusively war-related crimes, at the
U.N. conference in Rome from June 15 to July 17.
</P>
<P>
Unlike the Hague Tribunal, which only passes legal judgments,
the new court will indict, pass sentence and punish war criminals.
</P>
<P>
Some European countries demand that the soon-to-be established
court should put land mines on the list of banned weapons, and
that those who use them should be punished for war crimes.
</P>
<P>
But other countries, including the United States, oppose such a
detailed list of banned weapons. They prefer comprehensive, not
specific, regulations on weapons.
</P>
<P>
South Korea has been opposed to signing a worldwide treaty on
banning anti-personnel land mines. The mines, it said, have been a
integral part of its national defense for half a century.
</P>
<P>
About one million mines are believed to be buried along the
Demilitarized Zone, which is four kilometers wide and 249
kilometers long, and divides the Korean Peninsula into two parts.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
