<HEADLINE> Malaria Kills 6,000 Angolans Yearly </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, June 11 (Xinhua) -- Malaria has come up to be the No.
1 killer in Angola, claiming 6,000 lives each year, a senior
Angolan official has said.
</P>
<P>
Filomeno Fortes, Director for the Malaria Prevention Planning
Agency, revealed the figure Wednesday at the closing ceremony of
a seminar on the diagnosing, curing and prevention of malaria
held in Cacauco near Luanda.
</P>
<P>
He said that about 6,000 died of malaria each year among the
three million sufferers who went to see doctors for the disease.
</P>
<P>
The tropical weather, plus the bad sanitation condition
resulting mainly from the long years of civil war, have lead to
the fast spread of the disease, he said.
</P>
<P>
He said that the above-mentioned toll figure is only the
registered number from hospitals. The actually malaria figure
could be much bigger as many who suffer from malaria simply
didn't go to hospital.
</P>
<P>
The seminar, Fortes said, is part of the joint efforts by the
World Health Organization and the Angolan government to prevent
malaria.  
</P>
</TEXT>
