<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Transparency New Focus in China's Rural Democracy (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
"Over the past decade most Chinese villages have held three
direct elections of village officials, and the concept
of 'democratic election' has become deeply rooted in many farmers'
minds," said Zhang the director.
</P>
<P>
However, he conceded that efforts made to improve democracy in
village management remain far from enough nationwide.
</P>
<P>
The idea of promoting open management of village affairs was
formally promulgated in 1994, but only half of the villages in
China have adopted this system so far, he noted.
</P>
<P>
"No matter how democratic and successful a village election is,
if the farmers' democratic rights to take part in and monitor
village management can't be guaranteed, the democracy which
emerges will just be incomplete, fragile and short-lived," Zhang
stressed.
</P>
<P>
He went on to say that, apart from adding impetus to the
building of democracy, the system of open management of village
affairs will also effectively reinforce the anti-corruption
efforts by the Party and the government.
</P>
<P>
"An extensive fight against corruption in the vast countryside
will exert a great influence on the entire nation," he noted.
</P>
<P>
The system of open management of village affairs will not only
deter dishonest officials from trying to seek personal benefits
with their power, but also serve as a channel of mutual
understanding between the officials and the people, he added.
</P>
<P>
"Therefore, it can help improve the image of the Party and the
government in the farmers' minds, and promote reform, development
and stability in the rural areas," he concluded.  
</P>
</TEXT>
