<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China to Improve Taxation Law </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 11 (Xinhua) -- China's top legislature today
urged concerned government departments to speed up drafting the
revision of the current taxation law.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Standing Committee of the Ninth National
People's Congress (NPC) plans to check the enforcement of the Law
on the Administration of Taxation in July.
</P>
<P>
The NPC Standing Committee today called together senior
officials of the Ministry of Finance, the State General
Administration of Taxation and the Supreme People's Court to
discuss how to improve the country's taxation system.
</P>
<P>
The Law on the Administration of Taxation, which was adopted in
1993, is aimed at securing a continuous, steady growth of revenue
for the country.
</P>
<P>
"The total taxation revenue in the past five years was valued
at 2.75 trillion yuan (about 331 billion US dollars)," said Lu
Renfa, deputy commissioner of the General Administration of
Taxation.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that the taxation value has increased by 17.5
percent annually in the past five years.
</P>
<P>
Law enforcement organs throughout the country punished more
than 6.47 million tax evaders and other related offenders between
1993 and 1997.
</P>
<P>
The country has already established the tax declaration
system. "The awareness of paying taxes has greatly improved among
the people, and effective checks have reduced the amount of tax
evasion," said Gao Qiang, assistant minister of finance.
</P>
<P>
The traditional planned economy in China made the Chinese
people lack the awareness of paying taxes. Moreover, some taxation
bodies sometimes only loosely enforced the law. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
