<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Netanyahu Ponders Referendum on Withdrawal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, June 11 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin
Netanyahu Thursday hinted at holding a national referendum on
further Israeli troop withdrawal from the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
Before his meeting with visiting Australian Foreign Minister
Alexander Downer, Netanyahu told reporters that taking the issue
to the public is "one of the possibilities" aimed at making a
decision on further withdrawal.
</P>
<P>
He said that Israel is making efforts to reach an agreement
with the Palestinians on the scope of the pullback, over which the
peace talks between two sides have been stalled for more than a
year.
</P>
<P>
But he demanded reciprocity from the Palestinians so as to
advance the peace process, saying the Palestinian National
Authority (PNA) must take measures to ensure the security
interests of the Jewish state.
</P>
<P>
The PNA has accepted a United States proposal calling on Israel
to hand over 13.1 percent more of the West Bank in the second
stage pullback under the signed agreement between the Palestinians
and Israel.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu, however, rejected the proposal. The right-wingers in
the ruling Likud coalition even threatened to bring down the
government if Netanyahu agrees to yield more than 9 percent to the
Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
Under pressure from the U.S. and the world, some members of the
Knesset (Parliament) have suggested that Netanyahu could bypass
the cabinet by holding a referendum on the issue. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
