<DOCNO> XIE19980611.0086 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Scientists List 100 Major Scientific Puzzles </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 11 (Xinhua) -- One hundred major scientific
puzzles were listed for the first time by 118 Chinese scientists,
including 25 academicians of the Chinese Academy of Sciences (CAS).
</P>
<P>
A collection of papers on the 100 topics such as substance
structure, mechanics-turbulence, extraterrestrial civilization and
migrating to space and earthquake mechanism, were published today
by the Jilin People's Publishing House, which is named 100
Scientific Puzzles in the 21st Century.
</P>
<P>
"All the 100 scientific puzzles were selected from the
frontier of basic science researches. Most of them belong
to the science of nature, and some have much to do with the social
science especially philosophy," said Li Xixian, head of the
selecting group and an official with the CAS.
</P>
<P>
Zhou Guangzhao, vice-chairman of the Standing Committee of the
National People's Congress and former president of the CAS, said
that the listing of the scientific puzzles will greatly push forward
China's scientific research, since "asking questions is the first
step of making progress."
</P>
<P>
"Currently many researchers put their attention only onto minor
issues. As a result, their findings cannot bring the nation's
science research to a new level," he said. "We should focus more
efforts on these major scientific puzzles so as to make more
breakthrough."
</P>
<P>
At a meeting marking the publication of the book 100 Scientific
Puzzles in the 21st Century, Lin Quan, an official with the
Ministry of Science and Technology, said that while the external
conditions for scientific research are getting better and better
in China, encouraging the spirit of blazing new trials has come to
be the most important thing.
</P>
<P>
"The listing of the 100 scientific puzzles will help encourage
more pioneering work and new ideas," he said.
</P>
<P>
A deputy editor-in-chief from the Jilin People's Publishing
House said at the meeting that the development of sciences in
China needs more concerns from the national and the society.
</P>
<P>
"We hope that in the next century more scientific puzzles will
be settled by Chinese scientists, we hope that in the next century
China can have the honor to have its own Nobel Prize winners," he
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
