<HEADLINE> Syria Urges Ending Arab Normalization with Israel </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAMASCUS, June 11 (Xinhua) -- Syria urged the Arab countries to
commit themselves to the decisions made by the 1996 Arab summit,
which call for a halt of normalization with Israel if it fails to
fulfill its obligations.
</P>
<P>
"Syria believed such commitments are preconditions to make the
proposed Arab summit a success," a Syrian diplomatic source, who
asked not to be named, said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinian National Authority (PNA) and Syria are
spearheading an effort for a common Arab stance to confront the
hardline Israel after it failed to accept a U.S. formula on troop
redeployment in the West Bank, which is widely seen as a way to
get the Israeli-Palestinian peace talks back on track.
</P>
<P>
The formula calls on Israel to pull back its troops from 13
percent more of the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
Citing security reasons, Israel has so far boycotted the
proposal.
</P>
<P>
Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat began to push for an Arab
summit to adopt an unified stance toward Israel's intransigence
shortly after Israel refused to buy the U.S. compromise formula.
</P>
<P>
But the proposed Arab summit is still just on paper due to the
differences among the Arab states over how to deal with Israel
and the reported U.S. pressure for delaying the summit.
</P>
<P>
Syria, PNA and some more want to see a hardline Arab stance
while some others, such as Egypt and Jordan, favor a more moderate
approach. 
</P>
</TEXT>
