<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Transparency New Focus in China's Rural Democracy (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 11 (Xinhua) -- Having promoted democracy in the
rural areas for a decade, the Chinese government is now shifting
its focus from holding direct elections of village leadership to
ensuring greater transparency in village management and tighter
supervision of village officials by local people.
</P>
<P>
Major Chinese news media today published a circular jointly
issued by the Central Committee of the Communist Party of China
and the State Council, the country's cabinet, which requires the
country's nearly one million villages to adopt a system called
"open management of village affairs".
</P>
<P>
Under this system, village officials are obliged to make
regular reports to the entire village on the village's financial
conditions and other major affairs that have an impact on the
local people's interests.
</P>
<P>
"It is a very important and timely document, which reflects the
central authorities' strong advocacy of an open and democratic
village management system," said Zhang Mingliang, director of the
Grassroots Power Building Department under the Ministry of Civil
Affairs.
</P>
<P>
Starting in 1988, the Chinese government required all village
officials to be directly elected by all the villagers, instead of
being appointed by governments at higher levels.
</P>
<P>
In the meantime, it also started to promote a system called
"villagers' self-government" in the countryside. The system
features "four democracies", namely, democratic election (of
village officials), democratic decision-making (in village
management), democratic management (of village affairs) and
democratic supervision (by the villagers over the village
leadership).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980611.0092 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Yen's Depreciation No Help to East Asian Economy: FM Spokesman </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 11 (Xinhua) -- Foreign Ministry spokesman Zhu
Bangzao today urged Japan and countries related to take
effective measures to prevent the Japanese yen devaluating further.
</P>
<P>
The yen's consistent depreciation will not help stabilize the
present financial turmoil in the East Asia financial market, Zhu
said at today's routine press conference.
</P>
<P>
Japan and other countries with influence in the Asian financial
sphere should face the facts with courage and wisdom, make their
co-operation closer and create the necessary conditions for the
restoration of the regional economy, he said.
</P>
<P>
Considering the position of the Japanese economy and the yen in
the world economy, China is extremely concerned about the yen's
recent consistent depreciation against the US dollar, which has
caused another round of turmoil in the Southeast Asia financial
market, he said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, he reaffirmed that China's policy of keeping its
currency stable has not changed.
</P>
<P>
The East Asia financial crisis has caused some difficulties for
Hong Kong's economy, Zhu said, pointing to the fact that Hong
Kong's economic growth rate has slowed down, and the first quarter
even saw a decrease.
</P>
<P>
However, he pointed out, the basic factors of the Hong Kong
economy have remained sound, its foreign exchange reserve is
abundant and the financial administration mechanism is
healthy. Moreover, the economy in inland China has retained
sustained development, he said, expressing confidence that Hong
Kong's economy will shake off the present inconvenience.
</P>
<P>
The government of the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region
is undertaking measures to invigorate the local economy, and the
central government supports all its efforts in this regard,
including safeguarding the link between the Hong Kong dollar and
the US dollar, Zhu said.
</P>
<P>
To maintain Hong Kong's status as an international financial
center, it is important to keep their exchange rate stable, he
noted.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
