<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ruhe Blasts on Deteriorating Kosovo Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, June 11 (Xinhua) -- German Defense Minister Volker
Ruhe blamed Serbia on Thursday for attempting to "systematically
create a buffer zone between Kosovo and Albania."
</P>
<P>
The Serbian government, Ruhe said, resorted to regular armed
forces in ethnic cleansing by means of using tanks and artillery
indiscriminately against the civilian population in the Serbian
province of Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
The new level of violence was posing a threat to the security
and stability in the entire Balkan region, he told a North
Atlantic Treaty Organization (NATO) defense ministers meeting.
</P>
<P>
The NATO defense ministers were here to discuss military
options to stop the violence in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
Ruhe said political, economic and strategic means are needed to
influence Belgrade to stop forthwith the excessive use of force
against civilians and to withdraw its special police and armed
forces from Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
Belgrade should also be pressured into constructive dialogues
and negotiations in search for a peaceful solution, he said.
</P>
<P>
The NATO has decided to stage an air-land joint military
exercise in Albania before the end of August.
</P>
<P>
In addition, sources close to the NATO Military Committee said
the defense ministers are expected to announce new military
exercises to be held soon in Albania to demonstrate the visibility
of the alliance in the region.
</P>
<P>
The ministers were said to be considering air strikes and a
no-fly zone in Kosovo to force Belgrade into accepting the terms
the international community has set out.
</P>
<P>
Foreign ministers of the 15-nation European Union met on Monday
to enact bans on all new European investment in Serbia and a
freeze on Belgrade's state-held funds in EU countries as new
sanctions against Serbia.
</P>
<P>
Already in force are arms embargo and delivery of police
equipment to Serbia.
</P>
<P>
The EU also appealed the NATO to accelerate the study process
of its military options.
</P>
<P>
NATO foreign ministers, in their council meeting late last
month, authorized the military branch of the alliance to study
what the NATO could do to help resolve the crisis.
</P>
<P>
NATO Secretary-General Javier Solana said after the foreign
ministers meeting that NATO did not rule out anything in its
pursuit for a solution to the Kosovo crisis. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980611.0096 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. African Bank Raises Lending Rates </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, June 11 (Xinhua) -- Absa, the biggest commercial
bank in South Africa, has announced to lift its lending rates and
mo lending rates by two percentage points, sparking fears
that chances for higher economic growth in the country would be
severely damaged.
</P>
<P>
Absa said Wednesday the lending rate will increase from 18.25
percent to 20.25 with effect from Thursday. Mortgage lending
rates go up as follows: new loans from June 11; existing loans
from July 1; and loans with a one month's notice period from
August 1.
</P>
<P>
For now, South Africa's major banks chose to remain
tight-lipped after Absa's announcement.
</P>
<P>
Most banks said they were still weighing their options.
However, speculation is that most of the banks will soon follow
suit.
</P>
<P>
"We are still considering our options and have not made a
decision yet," a spokesperson of the First National Bank said
soon after Absa's announcement.
</P>
<P>
Standard Bank's Eric Larsen also said: "We are not yet
prepared to issue a statement in that regard."
</P>
<P>
Claire Gebhard-Mann, General Manager of the Banking Council of
South Africa, said that banks had been hesitant to go the route
of lending rates hikes, but the hikes were the logical way to go,
given the current financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
Absa's increase comes a few weeks after South African Reserve
Bank (SARB) Governor Chris Stals asked banks not to up interest
rates, citing the stabilization of the Rand, the national
currency of South Africa.
</P>
<P>
The Rand, which fell to 5.20 Rand against one U.S. Dollar in
May, stablized to 5.11 Rand after the SARB increased its repo
rate, the rates at which the central bank lends to commercial
banks on May 26 to ward off speculators.
</P>
<P>
Last week the SARB cut the repo rate by half a percentage
point. The Rand fell to 5.1935 against U.S. dollar Wednesday
afternoon.
</P>
<P>
On Tuesday night Finance Minister Trevor Manuel also appealed
to banks not to increase their rates.
</P>
<P>
Local economists said the interest rate hike, though
temporary, will take a heavy toll on economic growth. They
forecast the rate of growth in gross domestic product this year
at a paltry one percent, compared with initial expectations of
about two percent and recent projections of more than 1.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
GDP growth next year can be as low as two percent to three
percent, compared with earlier hopes of about 3.5 percent,
economists said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
