<HEADLINE> China Makes Progress in Exploring Overseas Oilfields </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 11 (Xinhua) -- China has gained great headway in
exploring overseas oilfields and has been granted the rights to
contract, operate and hold shares in an increasing number of
oilfields in other countries, including Canada, Peru, and
Thailand.
</P>
<P>
So far, China has had an annual oil supply of 700,000 tons from
overseas oilfields which it has contracted to operate, either
wholly or partly, marking a major breakthrough in expanding the
international oil market.
</P>
<P>
And the establishment of the China Overseas Oil and Gas Co. Ltd,
a subsidiary of the China National Offshore Oil Corp (CNOOC), has
attracted close attention of the international oil circle.
</P>
<P>
CNOOC has by now purchased 32.58 percent of the stock from the
Indonesian Malacca Oilfield, becoming its largest
shareholder. China has obtained 400,000 tons of oil a year from
the Malacca Oilfield since 1994. And by now, CNOOC has taken back
all its investments.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, CNOOC has succeeded in expanding its technological
presence in the world oil market. The overseas projects taken on
by CNOOC include an offshore platform in the United Arab Emirates,
offshore oil drilling in Japan, and geophysical prospecting and
seismic data collection in some other countries.
</P>
<P>
Additionally, CNOOC experts have been invited to act as
technological advisors for oil exploration in Kazakhstan. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
