<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tension Builds up in Nigeria </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, June 11 (Xinhua) -- Tension is building up in Nigeria
as the government has warned pro-democracy groups to call off
their planned rally Friday to mark the annulled June 12, 1993
election.
</P>
<P>
In the southern metropolis of Lagos, which is center of
pro-democracy groups, police spokesman Young Arabame Wednesday
warned organizers of any rally without permit to be ready for the
consequences.
</P>
<P>
State Administrator Colonel Mohammed Marwa said the same day
that the proposed mass rally is unnecessary at the time when the
nation is mourning the death of late head of state, General Sani
Abacha.
</P>
<P>
Instead, he called on the groups to embrace the hand of
friendship extended to Nigerians, including those in self-exile,
by the new leader, General Abdulsalam Abubakar, who has promised
to continue Abacha's transition to civil rule program.
</P>
<P>
The administrator warned that the security agencies are ready
to ensure that peace and tranquillity of the state are not
disturbed under any guise.
</P>
<P>
He urged all law-abiding citizens to go about their lawful
businesses Friday with the confidence that the government has the
capacity and the will to prevent any unlawful demonstration or
breakdown of law and order throughout the state.
</P>
<P>
However, he said that he will prefer, at this period of
national mourning, to avoid any situation that will necessitate
the use of force.
</P>
<P>
Despite Abubakar's pledge to continue the transition program
in his maiden national broadcast Tuesday night, pro-democracy
groups have criticized the speech as vague and empty, failing to
address key issues such as June 12 and political detainees.
</P>
<P>
The groups now demand that the government forgets about the
transition program. Instead, they want a national unity
government headed by Moshood Abiola, the widely-expected winner
of the 1993 election now in jail.
</P>
<P>
The Joint Action Committee of Nigeria (JACON), an umbrella of
52 pro-democracy groups, has called for mass rallies Friday
throughout the country to mark the 5th anniversary of June 12.
</P>
<P>
At a press conference Wednesday in Lagos, the organization
said, "Traders should lock up their shops and markets. Students
should boycott lectures. Drivers and road transport owners
should keep their vehicles off the road. Churches and mosques
should encourage their members to join the peaceful mass
rallies." 
</P>
</TEXT>
