<HEADLINE> Kenyan Govt Warns over Ozone Depleting Substances </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, June 11 (Xinhua) -- The Kenyan government has warned
of adverse effects through ozone depleting substances in the east
African country, calling for a controlled production and use of
chemicals concerned.
</P>
<P>
Currently the nation consumes a total of 600 tons of the ozone
depleting substances which entails use of about 300 tons of
methyl bromide in protection of food grains in stores, local
press reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
"We must strike the balance between the two (protections of
food and ozone layer) by having alternative storage chemical,
that is environmentally friendly," said Jesse Maia, the
assistance minister for environmental conservation, on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
"Indeed, we must protect our food, but ozone layer is equally
important," he told a one-day seminar.
</P>
<P>
"A number of chemicals including methyl bromide and some other
man-made chemicals are directly involved in destroying the ozone
layer faster than it is formed naturally," said Maia.
</P>
<P>
"If the controls recommended by the Montreal Protocol are
followed, it is predicted that the stratospheric ozone layer
would recover by about 2030, he said.
</P>
<P>
He added that his ministry is preparing a draft Environmental
Management Protection Bill which would be tabled in parliament
soon. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
