<HEADLINE> Information Technology to Be Boosted in East Africa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, June 11 (Xinhua) -- Some 18 billion Shillings (295
million U.S. Dollars) will be invested in information technology
in the east African region this year, the BMI Techknowledg
Africa has announced in a survey.
</P>
<P>
Kenya will have half of the total investment followed by
Tanzania with 30 percent and Uganda with the rest, the survey was
quoted by local press reports as saying Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The East Africa Information Technology Survey, the first of
its kind in the region, said that two thirds of the new
investments in information technology will be spent on public and
private telecommunications sectors.
</P>
<P>
It said that the telecommunications infrastructure of Kenya is
low with less than one line for every 100 people.
</P>
<P>
The density is, however, higher compared to some other African
countries with a density of 0.4 percent of the population. South
Africa is the exception with over 10 lines for every 100 people.
</P>
<P>
"Customers have access to a wider and internationally more
competitive array of services in Tanzania and Uganda, where
private sector is servicing strategic niche markets which are
vitally important especially for multi-national companies," the
survey said.
</P>
<P>
The survey said that although revenue per phone line in Kenya
is nearly 15 percent higher than the sub-regional average,
productivity per employee was over 30 percent below the regional
average and less than half of the average for all of Africa.
</P>
<P>
Currently there are about 8,000 Internet users in Kenya, 20
percent of them home users, according to the survey.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
