<DOCNO> XIE19980611.0104 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UNSCOM Chairman Arrives in Baghdad </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, June 11 (Xinhua) -- Richard Butler, chairman of the
United Nations Special Commission (UNSCOM) in charge of
dismantling Iraq's weapons of mass destruction, arrived here on
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Butler and the delegation accompanying him arrived at the
Habbaniya military airport, 80 kilometers west of Baghdad at noon.
</P>
<P>
The UNSCOM chairman is expected to hold talks with Iraqi
Deputy Prime Minister Tariq Aziz on tasks Iraq has to fulfill in
order to get the U.N. economic sanctions lifted. He will leave
here next Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Butler paid his last visit to Baghdad late March. U.N. arms
inspectors entered Iraq's presidential sites on the same day he
left here but found no prohibited weapons.
</P>
<P>
Earlier this month, when Butler briefed the U.N. Security
Council on his bi-annual technical report on Iraq's weapons of
mass destruction, he gave a list of priority tasks that Iraq has
to fulfill.
</P>
<P>
The priority tasks, called as a "road map" for Iraq to follow
to secure the lifting of the crippling sanctions against it,
requires Iraq to meet fully its obligations to provide access to
all necessary materials, documents and information concerning the
areas of ballistic missiles, chemical and biological weapons.
</P>
<P>
Butler reportedly said if Iraq can give the highest quality of
cooperation in this regard, UNSCOM can present the Security
Council a report in October that will be quite different from the
previous ones, and UNSCOM can move its work faster.
</P>
<P>
UNSCOM must certify that all Iraq's chemical, biological
weapons and ballistic missiles have been accounted for and
destroyed before the Security Council can consider lifting the
sanctions that have been in place since Iraq invaded Kuwait in
1990. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
