<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 30 km Electric Fence Removed from </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, June 11 (Xinhua) -- Botswana is dismantling a
30-km long electric fence along Botswana-Namibia border, informed
sources reaching here said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Work on rolling back a section of the killer barrier in
Ngamiland in northern Botswana, started more than two weeks ago,
the sources said.
</P>
<P>
The erection of the electric fence along the border,
stretching from Caprivi's Mahango Game Reserve to the Kwando
River, resulted in game, including elephants, giraffes, buffalos
and kudus, suffering a tortur death after getting entangled in
the fence during migration between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Concerns were raised in Botswana and Namibia over the
disruption of natural migratory routes and the impact on the
tourism industry.
</P>
<P>
Namibia reportedly launched a top-level probe into the
negative impact of the fence last year and also raised the issue
with the Botswanan government.
</P>
<P>
Local newspaper the Citizen quoted Botswana's Director of
Animal Health and Production M. V. Raborokgwe as saying that his
department had been instructed to take down a section of one of
the recently erected cordon fences in Ngamiland, in order to open
up the seasonal wildlife migration route.
</P>
<P>
Only the 30-km Northern Buffalo-Kwando River fence will be
taken down, Raborokgwe said.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that Botswana and Namibia had agreed that only
wild animals and not cattle be allowed to move freely.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
