<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sabotage to Derail German Train in March Confirmed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, June 11 (Xinhua) -- The German government confirmed
Thursday that a high-speed train nearly derailed on March 14 after
someone deliberately placed slabs of concrete on the tracks.
</P>
<P>
However, as reported by the German daily newspaper Bild earlier
in the day, the incident was just one of 40 attempts to sabotage
rail traffic in Germany since the start of this year.
</P>
<P>
The InterCity Express (ICE), Germany's fastest train with a top
speed of 280 kilometers an hour, ran into the obstacles and
swayed, but did not jump the tracks, the newspaper said.
</P>
<P>
Confirming the newspaper report, an Interior Ministry spokesman
said a list of registered railroad sabotages was compiled after
the occurrence of the country's worst rail tragedy on June 3.
</P>
<P>
In the latest incident, the exact cause of which is yet to be
determined, an ICE train derailed and crashed into a road bridge
near the northern German town of Eschede, killing over 90 people.
</P>
<P>
Investigators are suspecting a broken wheel as the most likely
cause, but still have to make clear how the crash has occurred.
</P>
<P>
The deadly crash considerably undermined the public trust in
the ICE train, which had had a perfect safety record since coming
into service in 1991. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
