<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Imported Car Sales Down Sharply in S. Korea </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, June 11 (Xinhua) -- Only 798 foreign cars were sold in
South Korea in the first five months of this year, against 3,977
units in the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
However, the Korean Automobile Manufacturers Association said
Thursday, the market share of U.S. cars grew 14.3 percentage
points from the 51.5 percent in the same period of 1997.
</P>
<P>
Among U.S. automakers, Chrysler enjoyed a 37.5 percent share of
the total foreign car sale with 299 units, followed by Ford with
219 units, or 27.4 percent, and General Motors with one.
</P>
<P>
General Motors sold 225 cars at the same time of last year.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, all European automakers, including Mercedes Benz,
BMW and Audi (Volkswagon) of Germany, and Volvo of Sweden, and
Japanese ones, saw their market shares plummeting.
</P>
<P>
U.S. cars outsold the European and Japanese ones because their
prices were more reasonable for the South Koreans who are still
haunted by the crisis-ridden economy, said the auto association.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
