<DOCNO> XIE19980611.0118 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dollar Climbs to 142 Yen in Tokyo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, June 11 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. dollar climbed at one point to
142.10 yen in Tokyo on Thursday, a level last seen in September 1990,
as the Japanese currency was bogged down by regional stock market
plunges.
</P>
<P>
The dollar was quoted at 141.67-70 yen at 5 p.m. (local time), up
from 141.43-45 yen at 9 a.m., and from 141.50-60 yen late Wednesday in
New York.
</P>
<P>
The dollar hit the day's high just after 3:00 p.m., a level not
seen since September 6, 1990 as sentiment for the yen was dampened
after the key Nikkei index on the Tokyo Stock Exchange lost more than
320 points in the afternoon.
</P>
<P>
Market players looked to exchange their devalued yen for "safe"
dollars for investments abroad, a mood enhanced by falling stock
markets in Asia, dealers said.
</P>
<P>
In addition, market players reacted with more pessimism after data
released Thursday by the Economic Panning Agency (EPA) indicated that
corporate capital spending will be depressed for the next six to nine
months.
</P>
<P>
Sentiment for the yen will likely be further damaged by Friday's
release of Japan's gross domestic product (GDP) for the
January-to-March period, dealers said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
