<DOCNO> XIE19980611.0121 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Owls Used to Save Paddy From Rodents in Malaysia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, June 11 (Xinhua) -- The northeastern state of
Terengganu in Malaysia is using owls to save paddy from rodents
which attack paddy fields.
</P>
<P>
So far more than 380 nests have been created for owls in rice
bowl areas like Setiu and Besut in the state, which saved some
4,800 tons of paddy of the first crop, worth 4.8 million ringgit
(1.215 million U.S. dollars), Malaysia's national news agency
Bernama reported Thursday quoting the state's Agriculture
Department Director Sofian Mohd Salleh.
</P>
<P>
This rodent control method would also be used in the areas of
Kuala Terengganu, Marang and Dungun with the creation of 100 nests
this year, Sofian said.
</P>
<P>
The official said the method also allowed farmers to breed
fresh-water fish in their paddy fields following reduced usage of
pesticides against the rodents.
</P>
<P>
At present, the Terengganu state produces 47,000 tons of paddy
per season. 
</P>
</TEXT>
