<HEADLINE> Major News Items in Leading French Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, June 11 (Xinhua) -- The following are major news items in
leading French newspapers on Thursday:
</P>
<P>
Liberation:
</P>
<P>
-- To the surprise of all, the pilots of Air France and the
management Wednesday reached an agreement, which foresees to keep
the status quo of the salaries of pilots for seven years and a
five-year program to pay young pilots a specific salary. The strike
has cost Air France more than one billion francs (167 million U.S.
dollars) and has relaunched the debate on privatization of the air
company.
</P>
<P>
-- The international community has hardened its tone against
Yugoslavia. The six member countries of the Contact Group on former
Yugoslavia threatened on Wednesday to impose new sanctions on
Belgrade if it does not put an end to its conflict with Kosovo
immediately.
</P>
<P>
Le Figaro:
</P>
<P>
-- After nine days of strike, the management of Air France and
the National Syndicate of Pilots of Airlines signed an agreement on
Wednesday to put an end to the conflict. The management yields to
almost all demands of the pilots, except that the salaries of the
pilots will be maintained at the present level for seven years.
</P>
<P>
-- The Minister of National Education Claude Allegre is preparing
a plan to ban teachers from being absent from their classes and
replace those who are frequently absent from their students in high
schools. 
</P>
</TEXT>
