<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> High Auto Emissions Banned in Romania </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUCHAREST, June 10 (Xinhua) -- The Romanian government has a
plan to ban vehicles with emissions higher than the European
standard into the country's auto market.
</P>
<P>
As announced by Romania's official television station Wednesday
evening, the measure taken by the Ministry of Transportation will
be effective from July 1 this year.
</P>
<P>
Also mandatory is that Romanian auto-makers will have to,
starting January 1, 1999, comply with the low emissions standard
of the European Union (EU).
</P>
<P>
All sub-standard locally made vehicles will no longer be
allowed to register after January 1, 2000.
</P>
<P>
The government measure is prompted by the deterioration of air
quality in urban areas across Romania, where an increasing number
of vehicles are hitting the street.
</P>
<P>
The problem, as explained by Ioan Tiganas, an official in
charge of vehicle registry in Romania, was partly due to the
importing of used cars in recent years.
</P>
<P>
Average 12 years in service, vehicles now in operation in
Romania are usually far below the latest emissions standard,
making them a major source of air pollution.
</P>
<P>
The ban on sub-standard vehicles are expected to help curb the
importing of used foreign cars while the authorities are putting
up a list of compliant car models. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
