<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-11 09:39 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Beirut Pressured to Accept Israeli Withdrawal Plan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, June 11 (Xinhua) -- The pro-Israeli militia the South
Lebanese Army (SLA) Thursday warned the Lebanese government of
grave consequences if it continues to reject Israel's offer on
conditional withdrawal from south Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
In a statement published on the Daily Star, the SLA said that
Lebanese government's blanket rejection of the Israeli offer would
force Israel to leave South Lebanon unilaterally and lead to a
bloody war between the SLA and the anti-Israeli forces.
</P>
<P>
"If it is effected, it will lead to a bloody war between the
SLA and the residents of the region against those who claim to be
resisting," the statement said, adding that the SLA could also
clash with the Lebanese army and eventually cause another Israeli
invasion.
</P>
<P>
Israel, in alliance with the SLA, has been occupying
1,200-square-kilometer border strip in south Lebanon since 1985
after two invasions.
</P>
<P>
With an average of 35 soldiers being killed there annually and
under mounting domestic pressure, Israel decided on April 1 to
pull out of the "death trap," provided security arrangements are
worked out with Beirut, including the safety of the 2,500 SLA
militiamen.
</P>
<P>
Lebanon flatly rejected the offer, insisting that the
withdrawal should be unconditional as stipulated in the
U.N. resolution 425, which Israel had been rejecting over the past
20 years.
</P>
<P>
The SLA statement appeared to be part of the continued efforts
of Israel to put more pressure on the Lebanese government to
accept the Israeli plan.
</P>
<P>
The Iranian-backed Hezbollah (Party of God) has been leading a
guerrilla war to oust Israeli troops from the Israeli
self-proclaimed security zone. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
