<HEADLINE> Share Prices Continue Plunging in Tokyo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, June 11 (Xinhua) -- Stock prices plunged for the second
straight day in Tokyo Thursday on continued worries about major
Japanese banks, the sputtering Asian economies and the falling yen.
</P>
<P>
The Nikkei Stock Averagy of 225 selected issues on the First
Section of the Tokyo Stock Exchange lost 325.22 points, or 2.12
percent, from Wednesday's close to end at 15,014.04.
</P>
<P>
The broader-based Tokyo Stock Price Index (TOPIX), covering all
First Section issues, slid 19.79 points, or 1.65 percent, to end at
1,178.81.
</P>
<P>
Turnover on the major section went up to an estimated 400 million
shares from Wednesday's 353 million shares.
</P>
<P>
Nippon Steel was the day's most actively traded issue.
</P>
<P>
Traders said pessimism on the market are growing due to the
deflating Japanese economy, falling share prices in Hong Kong and the
ever-weakening yen.
</P>
<P>
Market sentiment was also dampened by Thursday's announcement that
April machinery orders in Japan in the private sector fell 16.8
percent from the previous month and an unadjusted 17.8 percent from a
year earlier, they said. The figures are considered an early indicator
of trends in corporate capital spending over the six to nine months to
come.
</P>
<P>
Of the 1,336 issues listed on the First Section, losers outweighed
gainers 858 to 248, with 152 issues remaining unchanged. 
</P>
</TEXT>
