<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Increasing IPR Protection at Southern Chinese Customs-House </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHENZHEN, June 11 (Xinhua) -- Shenzhen Customs, in south
China's Guangdong Province, will do more to protect intellectual
property rights for domestic and overseas businesses.
</P>
<P>
Since China adopted the Customs Regulations on Protecting
Intellectual Property on October 1, 1995, Shenzhen Customs
officers have taken IPR protection as their major job, according
to Zhou Jizhong, deputy chief of the branch.
</P>
<P>
By May, the customs had uncovered more than 200 copyright,
trademark, and patent violations and cases of compact disc piracy
in a two-year period, and confiscated and destroyed over 3.2
million pirated CDs.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. Motion Picture Association, the International
Federation of the Phonographic Industry and the Business Software
Alliance commended the customs house for its work.
</P>
<P>
The officers use a machine that can accurately distinguish
source discs from others, allowing officers to seize source discs
that are being smuggled into China for illegal copying.
</P>
<P>
The customs house also tries to safeguard the interests of
domestic enterprises. Since July 1997, it has seized 5.6 million
yuan (about 670,000 U.S. dollars) worth of fake cloth that bore
brand-name product markings. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
