<HEADLINE> Increasing Forest Belts On Yangtze's Middle And Upper Reaches </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XINING, June 11 (Xinhua) -- Shelter belts have been planted on
the middle and upper reaches of the Yangtze River, adding 100,000
hectares of forest to the high-altitude region.
</P>
<P>
The shelter belts are being planted to prevent ecological
deterioration in the Yangtze River valley on a
160,000-square-kilometer area, and to maintain ecological
stability.
</P>
<P>
A 4,400-hectare, mainly on the Qinghai-Tibetan Plateau at an
average altitude of 4,000 meters, has been planted.
</P>
<P>
The Qinghai Forestry Bureau has organized over 30,000 local
people each year for tree planting, since the project began in
1990, says Liu Tianzhu, a Forestry Bureau official.
</P>
<P>
A "green protection sphere" has been set up in the region, with
a 40-hectare nursery for young plants and 20,000 forest protection
spheres.  
</P>
