<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Village Benefiting From The Great Wall </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 11 (Xinhua) -- Although hardly anyone knew its
name a decade ago, the village of Mutianyu, tucked in the
mountains to the north of Beijing, has become one of the richest
around.
</P>
<P>
The secret of its success is simple enough: it was lucky enough
to be in the vicinity of the Mutianyu section of the Great Wall,
which has become one of the 16 most famous scenic spots around the
Chinese capital.
</P>
<P>
One of the villagers, Hao Wenxia, gets up very early every
morning with his wife to get to their stalls at the foot of the
Great Wall before tourists arrive. The couple are a bit of a
rarity, since they have two business licenses. He sells souvenirs
while his wife sells clothes.
</P>
<P>
The 36-year-old man told reporters that he had been quite happy
at his job in a local garment factory until 1988, when the
Mutianyu section of the Great Wall opened to tourists and he
decided to gamble and quit his job to go open a stall.
</P>
<P>
Then, as the tourists kept pouring in, his two shops soon
developed into a bigger business, bringing to his family over
20,000 yuan (2400 US dollars) a year, and sometimes as much as
50,000 yuan.
</P>
<P>
With that money, Hao built a new house equipped with running
water, solar heating, and a telephone. He also acquired a minibus.
</P>
<P>
According to Zhao Zhikui, head of the village, each of the 150
households there has a tourism-related business of one sort or
another.
</P>
<P>
Because foreign tourists are always considered a big source of
money, there has been an accompanying desire to learn foreign
languages among the villagers. At Mutianyu, tourists can be heard
bargaining with vendors in English, Japanese, Russian, French and
German.
</P>
<P>
In 1997, the villagers' income went up to 13,100 yuan, compared
with about 720 yuan before 1988. And, every family owns a
motorcycle, over 30 households have minibuses and cars, and at
least 20 of them have flats in urban parts of Beijing, and half of
them have bank accounts with as much as 100,000 yuan. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
