<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-11 08:47 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israeli Researchers Develop New X-Ray Method </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, June 11 (Xinhua) -- Israeli researchers have
developed a new type of detector plate for digital X-ray which can
provide instant computer readouts, cover large scanned areas and
greatly reduce the amount of radiation to patients.
</P>
<P>
The Jerusalem Post reported Thursday that the polycrystalline
mercuric iodide plates are expected to replace emulsion film
currently in use in X-ray radiology.
</P>
<P>
The plates can allow direct digital readouts in real time that
can be stored and handled by a computer, and the image can be
viewed on the screen and sent for consultation anywhere in the
world via the Internet.
</P>
<P>
The plates are relatively inexpensive, highly sensitive and can
produce excellent images, the paper said.
</P>
<P>
The research team from Jerusalem's Hebrew University Wednesday
received the Kaye Innovation Award, established by Issac Kaye of
England, a leading figure in the pharmaceutical industry there.
</P>
<P>
Professor Michael Schreiber, who heads the research team,
called the method a "breakthrough" in digitalization that will be
commercialized in the near future.
</P>
<P>
The plates can also be used in mammography, fluoroscopy or
dental imaging, as well as in other applications that require
large-area imaging detectors, such as astrophysics. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
