<HEADLINE> Shanghai Becoming Important For German Chemical Company </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, June 11 (Xinhua) -- Shanghai has been selected by
Germany's BASF as a strategic center to help the chemical giant
expand its business in China.
</P>
<P>
Shanghai's transportation network, business information,
up-to-date science and technology, and large number of senior
personnel have helped BASF make the decision. It will have a
series of business activities in Shanghai to help it build
production facilities across the country.
</P>
<P>
It will manage BASF's operations in China, provide information
and consulting, and train personnel.
</P>
<P>
Of BASF's 9 joint ventures in China, 5 are in Shanghai and have
nearly 280 million U.S. dollars worth of investment. It is expanding
its business in Shanghai and recently added two big joint ventures
that produce foodstuff, additives for animal feed, and dyes for
printing.
</P>
<P>
By the year 2003, BASF's investment in China will be about 6
billion DM, 5 times the current figure, and its sales are expected
to hit 12 billion yuan, 3 times the present level. 
</P>
</TEXT>
