<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippine Airlines to Resume Regular Flights </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, June 11 (Xinhua) -- The strike-bound Philippine
Airlines (PAL) said Thursday that it will resume regular, though
limited, scheduled services to 14 domestic points and four
international destinations Friday, the country's national day.
</P>
<P>
PAL management said in a statement that PAL will expand this
initial flight schedule in the coming months as it builds up its
pilot corps by taking in new recruits to replace the 620 striking
pilots.
</P>
<P>
The PAL management Wednesday unilaterally declared an end to
the crippling strike by its pilots belonging to the Airline Pilots
Association of the Philippines (ALPAP) which staged the walkout
last Friday.
</P>
<P>
The airlines said it is currently processing applications for
pilot positions that are now vacant after the striking pilots
abandoned their posts and defied the government's back-to-work
order Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Before the pilots union's wildcat strike, PAL was mounting an
average of 160 departures daily in its domestic network, flying to
39 points across the country.
</P>
<P>
Its international services used to cover 30 points in 17
countries. But the airlines can now only operate regular services
from Manila to Tokyo, Singapore, Hong Kong and San Francisco, and
vice-versa.
</P>
<P>
The ALPAP said they were striking to protest a 30-year-old
early retirement policy contained in a collective bargaining
agreement reached between the union and the management.
</P>
<P>
Describing the policy as unfair, the ALPAP said about 200
senior pilots will be forced to retire in coming years.
</P>
<P>
But the PAL management said that the policy was already agreed
by the union which also invoked it when it was in their favor.
</P>
<P>
The strike has dealt a heavy blow to PAL, the country's
national flag carrier, which claimed to have lost 1 billion pesos
(25.6 million U.S. dollars) during the five-day work stoppage.
</P>
<P>
The Department of Labor and Employment is still mediating
between the striking pilots and the PAL management. The department
said earlier it would rule on whether the PAL's decision to fire
the striking pilots is legal. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
