<HEADLINE> Australia Expecting More Tourists From China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, June 11 (Xinhua) -- People in Australia's tourism and
airline industries are encouraged by the growing number of Chinese
tourists visiting the country, which went up 23 percent to close
to 70,000 in 1997, according to the latest tourist administration
figures.
</P>
<P>
Australia has replaced the Singapore-Malaysia-Thailand tour as
the Chinese tourist's favorite choice, with the latter down 3.6
percent, because of the Southeast Asian financial crisis since
last October.
</P>
<P>
Australian tourist agencies have been trying to take advantage
of this with tourist promotions in China and by diversifying
services to attract more Chinese tourists.
</P>
<P>
Some airlines, like Ansett, Australia's second largest air
carrier, have increased the number of flights to meet the
increasing demand. It added a third flight to its Shanghai-Sydney
route in June 1997. Craig Wallace, manager of the company's
international department, says that its turnover in China last
year has greatly exceeded their expectations and it is planning to
do even better this year. 
</P>
