<DOCNO> XIE19980611.0163 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Fears Over Yen Send Asian Markets Plummet </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, June 11 (Xinhua) -- Stock and currency markets in Asia
tumbled in the past few days on continued uncertainty about the
Japanese economy.
</P>
<P>
Policy makers and financiers urged the Group of Seven (G-7)
industrialized nations to act to stem the continuing yen slide.
</P>
<P>
The Stock Exchange of Thailand (SET) index lost another 7.62
points to 284.48 at midday Thursday before plunging 16.15 points
or 5.2-percent from the previous day to close at 292.10.
</P>
<P>
It was the first time the SET index fell below the
psychological 300-point level in 11 years. Dealers said it was the
lowest closing record since 1987, when the SET began its bullish
run.
</P>
<P>
On Wednesday in Hong Kong, despite a rise in interbank interest
rates, the Hang Sen index lost 412.09 points, or 5 percent, to
close at 7,979.37 points, its lowest close since March 1995.
</P>
<P>
In Singapore, the key Straits Times industrial index plunged
4.4 percent to 1,067.81, the lowest level in seven years. Seoul
stock index similarly plunged 4.3 percent to 324.54 points.
</P>
<P>
The Japanese yen Wednesday fell to 141.5 against the U.S.
dollar, dragged down by investors' concerns that the G-7 deputy
finance ministers meeting in Paris would not take any concerted
action to halt the yen slide.
</P>
<P>
Further depressing sentiments were clear signs of a sharp fall
in the baht, which traded late Wednesday at 43.00/10 to the
dollar, against 42.90 Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Amaret Sila-On, chairman of the Stock Exchange of Thailand,
attributed the bearish atmosphere across the region to the
ineffective measures Japan has taken to spur its economy.
</P>
<P>
He also blamed the G-7 nations for failing to take a lead in
tackling the economic problems in the region.
</P>
<P>
The dependence on the Japanese economy could partly explain why
the yen slide was triggering a currency and stock avalanche across
Asia.
</P>
<P>
Japan, the major export market for many Asian nations as well
as the biggest investor in the region, projected its gross
domestic product (GDP) growth rate at only 0.23 percent this year.
</P>
<P>
The estimation caused the so-called "confidence crisis" among
Southeast and East Asian countries.
</P>
<P>
South Korea forecast that its GDP growth this year will
contract 2.2 percent, while Singapore also lowered its projection
of GDP growth from the previous 7.8 percent to 2.5 percent. Both
Malaysia and Hong Kong saw contraction in their GDP growth in the
first quarter of this year.
</P>
<P>
The fluctuation of the Asian currency markets has kept the
interest rates high, if not forcing them to go higher, aggravating
the liquidity crunch experienced by businesses in Asian countries.
</P>
<P>
In Thailand, local businessmen have long complained about the
high interest rates. The unaffordable high rates have pushed them
to the brink of collapse, they said.
</P>
<P>
However, the central bank, with the painful memory of the baht
depreciation last July still in mind, persisted in its stance of
keeping the rates high for fear of a free fall of the currency
under speculative attacks.
</P>
<P>
Some economists said that the yen depreciation has both
negative and positive implications for the economies of Thailand
and other Southeast Asian countries.
</P>
<P>
They hope with weaker currencies exports in these countries can
be boosted.
</P>
<P>
But export records in the past few months after currency
devaluation showed that lower prices were not as effective as the
governments had expected.
</P>
<P>
The governments must try hard to find the way out of the second
wave of crisis, as some named the current turmoil. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980611.0164 </DOCNO>
