<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-11 08:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iran's Economic Group in Cairo After 20 Years </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, June 11 (Xinhua) -- In another move to repair their
long-strained ties, a high-level Iranian economic delegation
arrived here early Thursday on a five-day trip to boost trade and
economic cooperation with Egypt.
</P>
<P>
The visit was the first of its kind in nearly two
decades. Relations between the two countries soured after Iran's
Islamic Revolution in 1979 and a dispute over former Egyptian
President Anwar Sadat's peacemaking with Israel.
</P>
<P>
The 25-strong Iranian delegation, which includes
representatives from the heavy industries, banks, commodity
sectors and members of the Iranian Chamber of Commerce, was
invited by Chairman of the Egyptian Industries Federation Abdel
Moneim Saudi.
</P>
<P>
The visit followed a similar trip to Iran by a delegation from
the Union of the Egyptian Industries in March this year, when the
two sides discussed prospects for holding an exhibition of
Egyptian products in Tehran.
</P>
<P>
This time the two sides are expected to discuss the preparatory
work for holding the planned exhibition in a bid to upgrade the
economic and trade relations.
</P>
<P>
The sluggish Egyptian-Iranian economic cooperation was the
bitter fruit of the strained diplomatic and political relations
between the two countries in the past 20 years.
</P>
<P>
Iran disrupted its political and economic ties with Egypt after
Sadat's historical visit to the arch enemy Israel to launch his
peace initiative in 1979.
</P>
<P>
Besides, Egypt accused the post-Islamic Revolution Iran of
backing Muslim militants fighting to overthrow Egypt's secular
government.
</P>
<P>
The ice in the Egyptian-Iranian relations has gradually thawed
in the recent years. The bilateral trade in 1997 amounted to 75
million U.S. dollars, with Egypt imports reaching 35 million
dollars and exports 45 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
Iran is currently investing 220 million Egyptian pounds (about
64.7 million dollars) in seven projects of weaving, carpets,
ready-made garments and banks in Egypt.
</P>
<P>
Iran's Charge d'Affaires in Cairo Akbar Kassemi has hailed the
new developments in Egyptian-Iranian relations as "a breakthrough."
</P>
<P>
One direct spur to their bilateral ties was the talks held by
then Iranian Foreign Minister Ali Akbar Velayati with senior
Egyptian officials during his visit to Cairo last year, he added.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980611.0166 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shanghai's State Enterprises Attracting Get Overseas Investment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, June 11 (Xinhua) -- Shanghai will push its large and
medium-sized state enterprises to raise international funds with a
goal of getting four billion U.S. dollars worth of overseas
investment this year.
</P>
<P>
Similar investment was down 10 percent in the first five months
compared with the same period last year, to 1.3 billion
U.S. dollars, although contracts for funds were up 40 percent to
2.6 billion U.S. dollars, according to Wan Junyi, an official from
the municipal overseas investment office, who attributes the
decrease to smaller cash flow from some Asian countries.
</P>
<P>
He says that projects needing overseas investment are valued at
over 100 billion yuan. The municipal government is encouraging
large and medium-sized state enterprises in packaging,
infrastructure and hi-tech industries to improve ties with
multinationals.
</P>
<P>
Shanghai is allowing overseas business people to purchase
companies, or merge with or lease them, or buy shares in smaller
state firms, about a hundred of which have been traded in this way
this year.
</P>
<P>
Wang also says that Shanghai is experimenting with overseas
investment in technological development and for tourist agencies
and even for education.  
</P>
