<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Protecting Snakes In China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, June 11 (Xinhua) -- The need to protect snakes was
discussed at a seminar that opened on Wednesday in the city of
Shanghai, sponsored by the Shanghai Wild Animal Protection
Association and the International Wild Animal Protection
Association.
</P>
<P>
Because of the money to be made, people continue to kill snakes
and have caused a decrease in their numbers. The city used to have
16 types of snakes around it, but now only five to six types can
be seen.
</P>
<P>
Roughly half of the city's 20,000 restaurants prepare snakes in
one way or another, helping to consume more than a thousand tons
of them a year.
</P>
<P>
Medical uses also increase the demand for snakes and they are a
popular item for export. Shanghai exports 250,000 tons of Pallas
pit vipers every year, earning 500,000 US dollars worth of foreign
currency.
</P>
<P>
Things are changing however. The city has put the 16 types of
snakes under protection and passed regulations to control the
snake business. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980611.0169 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Doctors Treat Sea Lion With Broken Jaw </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DALIAN, June 11 (Xinhua) -- A one-year old sea lion in the
Dalian Hutan Recreation Center's sea animal performance hall,
whose lower jaw was broken four days ago, has recovered health
with the help of doctors from an army hospital.
</P>
<P>
The wounded sea lion Linda was bought from Africa a year
ago. This female sea lion was bit by a male sea lion when the two
were playing in the afternoon of June 7.
</P>
<P>
It took doctors half an hour to complete the operation on
Linda, who now is in good health conditions.
</P>
<P>
The 3,000-square-meter sea animal performance hall, established
in 1990, now has five African sea lions, a rare animal species in
the world. 
</P>
</TEXT>
