<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 0900 GMT, June 11 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE -- The Zimbabwean Ministry of Higher Education and
Technology has ordered all striking students throughout the
country to be back in class by Thursday morning.
</P>
<P>
Deputy Minister Sikhanyiso Ndlovu warned in a statement
Wednesday that failure to heed the call would mean that the
students are not interested in studying, local press reported
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The ministry was against any form of violence that could lead
to the destruction of property and endangering of life, said the
statement. (Zimbabwe-Students' Demonstration)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
NEW DELHI -- The death toll in the deadly cyclonic storm that
lashed the west coast of India Tuesday has increased to 565,
according to reports from the cyclone-hit areas.
</P>
<P>
With the recovery of more bodies from the rubbles of flattened
houses and mazes of uprooted trees and electric poles in the
coastal areas, the toll would most likely increase.
</P>
<P>
Many of the victims and those missing are salt workers who were
washed away into the sea by the tidal waves rising from the Gulf
of Kutch. (India-Cyclone-Toll)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
NEW DELHI -- India has reminded the Group-8 countries, due to
meet in London Friday, of its "categorical rejection of any
suggestions" for curtailing its nuclear weapon or missile
development program.
</P>
<P>
In a statement issued Wednesday night, the Ministry of External
Affairs said India expected positive response to its initiatives
from the G-8 countries rather than "prescriptive and coercive
suggestions which are neither responsible nor constructive".
(India-Nuclear Program)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS -- The General Assembly of the United Nations on
Wednesday concluded a three-day Special Session and adopted three
documents on fighting the world drug problem.
</P>
<P>
The Special Session, also known as the "Drugs Summit," reviewed
previous policies against the illicit production, sale, demand,
trafficking and distribution of narcotics and psychotropic
substances and proposed new strategies to combat the problem.
</P>
<P>
A Political Declaration adopted at the session calls on member
states to commit themselves to significant and measurable results
in reduction of the illicit supply and demand for drugs by the
year 2008. (UN-Drug Session)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS -- United Nations Secretary-General Kofi Annan
Wednesday recommended the establishment of a U.N. observer mission
in Sierra Leone to help disarm the former ruling junta and support
the "fragile but vital process" of promoting civilian rule.
</P>
<P>
In his report to the U.N. Security Council, Annan said the
situation in Sierra Leone has in some respects improved
considerably. (UN-Sierra Leone-Mission)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BUENOS AIRES -- Paraguay's ruling Colorado Party candidate Raul
Cubas has been officially proclaimed as President of Paraguay,
according to news reports reaching here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The Superior Court of Electoral Justice (TSJE) made the
announcement on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
In the general elections conducted last month, Cubas got
887,196 votes, 55 percent of the total. He beat his Democratic
Alliance rival candidate Domingo Laino by a margin of 10 percent.
</P>
<P>
The result enables the ruling Colorado Party to continue its
50-year hold on power. (Paraguay-General Elections)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
ATHENS -- The Children's Forum 21 (CF21) was established
Wednesday in the Greek capital of Athens with the aim of promoting
effective change in the situation of children all over the world.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a press conference, Executive Council Chairperson
Isidora Papafragou said that inspired by the United Nations'
convention of the rights of the child, the international non-
governmental organization was set up to back the fundamental
rights of the children in the world, with the active participation
of young people and adults. (Greece-Children's Forum) 
</P>
