<HEADLINE> Zimbabwean Students Ordered Back to Class </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, June 11 (Xinhua) -- The Zimbabwean Ministry of Higher
Education and Technology has ordered all striking students
throughout the country to be back in class by Thursday morning.
</P>
<P>
Deputy Minister Sikhanyiso Ndlovu warned in a statement
Wednesday that failure to heed the call would mean that the
students are not interested in studying, local press reported
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The ministry was against any form of violence that could lead
to the destruction of property and endangering of life, said the
statement.
</P>
<P>
Students all over the country had been demonstrating for
increases in their grants and loans.
</P>
<P>
On Wednesday, the students went on the rampage in Bulawayo,
the country's second largest city, tearing and burning thousands
of newspapers and magazines at various selling points in the city
center.
</P>
<P>
In Gweru of central Zimbabwe, more than 1,000 students from
three tertiary institutions resumed their demonstrations to press
for increased payouts.
</P>
<P>
On the same day, police detained Job Sikhala, secretary
general of the Zimbabwe National Students Union, for three hours
for allegedly violating sections of the miscellaneous offences
act. 
</P>
