<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Southern Chinese Province Protecting Arable Land </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, June 11 (Xinhua) -- South China's Guangdong Province
had scored a success in protecting 2.56 million hectares of arable
land by the end of 1997.
</P>
<P>
The amount of arable land in Guangdong shrank 31,300
hectares in 1993, mostly because of real estate projects and golf
courses.
</P>
<P>
So, it began protecting arable land in 1995, and returned about
88 percent of the unused arable land to farming. The provincial
government drew up a proposal on protecting arable land and it now
has a protection zone of 1.36 million hectares.
</P>
<P>
The province also discovered 220,000 cases of illegal land use
of 54,667 hectares of land.
</P>
<P>
Since 1995, construction projects using arable land have been
kept to a minimum and there has been no new unused land in the
province in the past three years.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980611.0177 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Controlling Soil Erosion in Yangtze River Valley Pays off </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHONGQING, June 11 (Xinhua) -- Soil erosion controls on the
upper reaches of the Yangtze River are beginning to pay off after
a decade of work.
</P>
<P>
Some 53,000 square kilometers of eroded land, more than a fifth
of the total amount on the upper reaches, has been brought under
control.
</P>
<P>
The eco-system has improved a great deal in the area, as areas
around 2,200 small streams and ponds begin to turn green and the
grass and forest coverage rate goes from 22.8 percent to 41.1
percent. The amount of eroded land has been decreased by more than
70 percent.
</P>
<P>
Attending to the upper reaches of the Yangtze River was listed
by the State Council in 1988 as a key water and soil conservation
project, in 183 counties of 10 provinces and Chongqing
Municipality.
</P>
<P>
The central government has gradually increased spending on the
project. It spent 170 million yuan last year.
</P>
<P>
In the past decade, some 400,000 hectares of hillside land have
been transformed into terraced fields, and more than 2.2 million
hectares of forests have been planted with fruit trees and grasses
to control water and soil erosion. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
