<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Western Pacific Region to Be Leprosy-Free: WHO </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, June 11 (Xinhua) -- The World Health Organization (WHO)
Regional Office for the Western Pacific said Thursday that the
elimination of leprosy is likely in the region by the end of 1998.
</P>
<P>
In a press release, the Manila-based WHO regional office said
almost all the countries and areas in the region have eliminated
leprosy, a communicable disease which progresses inconspicuously
over years.
</P>
<P>
The office said that efforts will be intensified to help 11
lagging countries in the region to root out the disease, which the
WHO expects to be eradicated by the year 2000 globally.
</P>
<P>
At a three-day regional workshop on the elimination of leprosy
ending here Thursday, WHO Regional Director for the Western
Pacific S.T. Han called on the governments in the region to
sustain their political commitments to fighting leprosy.
</P>
<P>
He also urged the international community to continue its
financial and material support to the goal of rooting out the
disease.
</P>
<P>
The number of registered leprosy cases in the region is
continuously declining and has reached a low level of less than
25,000 among a population of 1.6 billion people, Han said.
</P>
<P>
The remaining problem of leprosy will be far more difficult as
it includes neglected areas, population groups and communities, he
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980611.0183 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zimbabwean Parliament Approves SADC Protocol on </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, June 11 (Xinhua) -- the Southern African Development
Community (SADC) protocol on trade has been ratified by
Zimbabwe's parliament, Zimbabwe's newspaper The Herald reported
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The protocol on trade which will help to further liberalise
regional trade in goods and services on the basis of fair,
mutually equitable and beneficial trade arrangements, was
ratified Wednesday by the Zimbabwean parliament.
</P>
<P>
The protocol was concluded in 1996 in Maseru, capital of
Lesotho.
</P>
<P>
Zimbabwe's Industry and Commerce Minister Nathan Shamuyarira,
who led parliament into ratifying the protocol, said that the
protocal will also contribute towards the improvement of the
climate for domestic, cross-border and foreign investment with
tariffs expected to progressively fall to zero within the next
eight years when the protocol comes into effect.
</P>
<P>
The protocol, which will be one of the major items to be
discussed at SADC's next summit in Mauritius this August, seeks
to enhance the economic development, diversification and
industrialisation of the region and to establish a free trade
area in the region. 
</P>
</TEXT>
