<DOCNO> XIE19980611.0185 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Worldwide PC Demand Lukewarm in Second Quarter </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, June 10 (Xinhua) -- Facing up with "a lukewarm
environment," unit volume in the worldwide personal computer (PC)
market this quarter is expected to grow 9 percent.
</P>
<P>
The environment, said a market researcher, is the result of a
downturn in the Asia-Pacific region, softness in the portable PC
market and problems in the supply channel in the United States.
</P>
<P>
By region, West Europe is likely to grow 14 percent on low-cost
PCs, improving economies in France and Germany and a greater focus
from global PC manufacturers, said International Data Corp. (IDC).
</P>
<P>
The U.S. market will see a similar growth rate in vendor unit
shipments, owing to a strong economy and the low-cost market.
</P>
<P>
However, IDC said in its latest report, in the United States
and other markets, severe price pressure will limit revenue and
profit growth for most PC vendors.
</P>
<P>
In addition, inventory problems have slowed channel ordering
and induced a more conservative stance on PC manufacturing in the
United States.
</P>
<P>
Demand in the Asian-Pacific region (excluding Japan) continues
to be weak, with Southeast Asian countries and South Korea showing
no signs of economic recovery, IDC said.
</P>
<P>
Adding fuel to the fire are the economic sanctions recently
placed on India.
</P>
<P>
Based on these market conditions, IDC expects unit shipments in
the second quarter to show slight negative growth in the region,
and the growth of the entire year to be 5 percent.
</P>
<P>
In Japan, IDC said, ongoing financial concerns and reduced
consumer demand will result in negative growth this quarter and
only two percent growth for the whole year.
</P>
<P>
Looking forward, there is little relief to the tough pricing
environment, IDC said.
</P>
<P>
While the inventory situation may improve, slower market
growth, expansion of the low-cost PC market and heightened
competition among central processing unit (CPU) suppliers will all
catalyze an ongoing price war, IDC concluded. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980611.0186 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Exporting Freon-Free Products </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANCHANG, June 11 (Xinhua) -- China's Huayi Group, a major
CFC-Free compressor and refrigerator producer, exported 15,000
freon-free refrigerators to 23 countries and regions in the first
five months of the year, up 39 percent from the same period last
year, giving China's freon-free products a place in the world.
</P>
<P>
The company, in Jingdezhen City in the northeastern part of
China's Jiangxi Province, opened in 1987, using Italian
technology, at a cost of 400 million yuan.
</P>
<P>
It is one of the first Chinese companies to produce a CFC-free
compressor and can now produce 5 million freon-free compressors
every year.
</P>
<P>
CFCs (chlorofluorocarbon) are a chemical compound that contains
freon, which damages the ozone layer of the atmosphere and has
been banned from most developed countries.
</P>
<P>
China has promised to phase out CFCs by 2005. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
