<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cyclone Toll Rises to 565 in West India </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, June 11 (Xinhua) -- The death toll in the deadly
cyclonic storm that lashed the west coast of India Tuesday has
increased to 565, according to reports from the cyclone-hit areas.
</P>
<P>
With the recovery of more bodies from the rubbles of flattened
houses and mazes of uprooted trees and electric poles in the
coastal areas, the toll would most likely increase.
</P>
<P>
Many of the victims and those missing are salt workers who were
washed away into the sea by the tidal waves rising from the Gulf
of Kutch.
</P>
<P>
The cyclone, which hit the coastal city of Porbandar, Gujarat
state, around 10:30 a.m. Tuesday and weakened Wednesday morning,
caused unprecedented destruction and paralyzed life in the hit
areas.
</P>
<P>
unconfirmed reports put the toll at over 1,000 with another
1,000 missing in the worst-hit Kutch area of Gujarat alone. The
state government evacuated more than 15,000 people to safer areas.
</P>
<P>
Thousands of houses were damaged and road and communication
links disrupted in the cyclone, and cities like Jamnagar,
Porbandar, Gandhidham, Bhuj and Khambhaliya in Gujarat were in
total darkness.
</P>
<P>
Initial estimates said the damage to property is around 12
billion rupees, or 300 million U.S. dollars, in Kutch and
Saurashtra areas.
</P>
<P>
Indian Prime Minister Atal Bihari Vajpayee appealed Wednesday
night to Indians and those of Indian origin living abroad to make
generous contributions to the relief work in the devastated areas.
</P>
<P>
Civil authorities, assisted by army and air force personnel,
began massive relief and rescue operations shortly after the
storm.
</P>
<P>
Indian Minister of State for Agriculture Sompal said Wednesday
in the parliament that the crisis management system at the
national level had been activated and the Union government was
maintaining a close contact with the three cyclone-hit state
governments.
</P>
<P>
The minister informed the parliament that the second
installment of relief fund of 290.3 million rupees (7.25 million
U.S. dollars) was released Wednesday in advance.
</P>
<P>
The first installment of the central share of calamity relief
fund of 804.4 million rupees (20.1 million dollars) for the
current year had already been released in April. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
