<HEADLINE> Bulls Edge Jazz in Game 4, One Step away from Title </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 10 (Xinhua) -- Michael Jordan and Scottie
Pippen joined hands to score 62 points as the Chicago Bulls edged
the Utah Jazz 86-82 in Game 4 of the NBA Finals, leading the
best-of-seven series 3-1 at the United Center of Chicago on
Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
It was the third straight loss for Utah, who beat Chicago in
Game 1 but slumped to a humiliated loss Sunday night.
</P>
<P>
The Bulls, who are bidding for third straight victory in the
Finals this decade, only one step away from the target. The next
game will be on Friday, still staged on their home floor, where
they have a 36-4 record.
</P>
<P>
Karl Malone hit 21 points and grabbed 14 rebounds, but was
totally shut down by Dennis Rodman in the final quarter. The ace
score of the Jazz only hooped two points and landed three boards,
clearly outnumbered by the "Worm", who showed enough nerve to put
in four balls at the line in the final minutes, and hauled off
four rebounds.
</P>
<P>
After routing Utah 42 points last Sunday, the Bulls enjoyed a
slight edge over their rivals all the way to wind up the first
half 39-37.
</P>
<P>
The score was seasawed mid-way into the third quarter and the
gap was kept within a range of four points. Jordan and Pippen
contributed 21 points each before the final quarter, with Malone
dominated the scoring board for Utah with 21 points.
</P>
<P>
But Malone played a unsteady game tonight, hit no point in the
entire second quarter, and almost repeated the no-show in the last
12 minutes.
</P>
<P>
The Bulls looked have a clear edge over the ailing Jazz, and a
successful sweep of the final triumph is within their reach.
</P>
<P>
It is not realistic for Utah to win the following three games
in a row, so Game 5 might be the last battle for the Bulls on
their way to win their sixth championship. 
</P>
</TEXT>
