<HEADLINE> Eastern Chinese Hub Port Construction </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
FUZHOU, June 11 (Xinhua) -- East China's Fujian Province
expects to build a port group and transport system with hubs at
Fuzhou, Xiamen, and Meizhou by the year 2010.
</P>
<P>
A Provincial Transport Department official says that by 2000,
Fujian will build 19 deepwater berths, bringing the total number
to fifty, with a total annual handling capacity of 68.53 million
tons. As many as 85 deepwater berths will be built by 2010, with a
total annual handling capacity of 200 million tons.
</P>
<P>
By the end of 1997, the province had 31 deepwater berths for
ships of 10,000 DWT, with a total annual capacity of 37.7 million
tons, and 730,000 TEUs, making Fuzhou and Xiamen two of the ten
largest ports in China. The annual handling capacity of Quanzhou
topped 10 million tons for the first time.
</P>
<P>
To keep up with foreign demand, Fuzhou, the provincial capital,
will increase construction, adding four or five deepwater berths,
and raising 200 million yuan for the dredging of the Minjiang
River waterway, and construction of the Jiangyin Port.
</P>
<P>
The province will use securities and shares to raise port
construction funds, open a port construction company, and use the
BOT (build-operate-transfer) method and World Bank loans.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
