<HEADLINE> Most Cambodian Voters Registered for Polls </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PHNOM PENH, June 11 (Xinhua) -- More than 80 percent of the
estimated 5.6 million Cambodian voters have registered for the
elections to be held in July, the Cambodia Daily reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The National Election Committee (NEC) was quoted as heralding
the success of the first three weeks of the month-long
registration, scheduled from May 18 to June 15, in spite of many
technical difficulties in the process.
</P>
<P>
The NEC figures put the number of voters registered in the
first and second weeks at more than 1.7 million and more than 1.5
million, respectively.
</P>
<P>
The third-week number has reached 688,132 according to the
statistics from only ten of the country's 20 provinces.
</P>
<P>
Prum Nhean, a NEC member, said that the final number of the
eligible voters would be slightly higher than the estimated with
the inclusion of Khmer Rouge defectors in the former rebel
stronghold of AnlongVeng.
</P>
<P>
Ten registration stations opened in the AnlongVeng area this
week, Prum Nhean said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the NEC acknowledged problems in the registration
process, such as multiple registrations, the registration of
non-Cambodian citizens and the collection of polling cards from
voters after they had registered.
</P>
<P>
NEC Chairman Chheng Phon warned Wednesday that anyone who
attempted to collect the cards would be punished according to the
law. Similarly, any electoral officials who deliberately
registered a non-Cambodian national or anyone who registered more
than once would be subject to a fine or other punishment. 
</P>
</TEXT>
