<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Myanmar's Agriculture Grows by 2.9 Percent in 1997-98 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, June 11 (Xinhua) -- Myanmar's agriculture grew by 2.9
percent in its output value in the 1997-98 fiscal year ended March
despite experience of flash floods and drought during the fiscal
year in some areas, according to the latest official statistics.
</P>
<P>
Agriculture, which is the mainstay of Myanmar's economy, has
traditionally accounted for 35 to 40 percent of the country's
total gross domestic product (GDP) and about 35 percent of its
export.
</P>
<P>
Its four major crops are designated as paddy, beans and pulses,
cotton and sugarcane, while other cash crops include rubber, palm
oil, jute, coffee, corn, mulberry and tea.
</P>
<P>
The paddy production of the country in the fiscal 1997-98 was
17.3 million tons, a little less than that of the previous year,
according to a report of the country's financial, economic and
social conditions issued by the Ministry of National Planning and
Economic Development.
</P>
<P>
The output of various beans and pulses reached 1.52 million
tons in the fiscal year, of which 660,773 tons were exported.
</P>
<P>
In the fiscal year, Myanmar imported 46,727 tons of wheat and
280,000 tons of chemical fertilizer, the report added.
</P>
<P>
The country produced 17.6 million tons of paddy with 100,400
tons of rice exported in the last 1996-97 fiscal year.
</P>
<P>
According to the report, Myanmar's GDP registered a 4.6 percent
growth in the 1997-98 fiscal year, lower than the set target of
6.4 percent. The average annual growth rate in the previous five
years (1992-93 to 1996-97) was 7.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
In the 1998-99 fiscal year, which began in April, the country's
GDP is set to increase by 6.2 percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
