<HEADLINE> India Rejects Proposals for Curtailing Nuclear Program </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, June 11 (Xinhua) -- India has reminded the Group-8
countries, due to meet in London Friday, of its "categorical
rejection of any suggestions" for curtailing its nuclear weapon or
missile development program.
</P>
<P>
In a statement issued Wednesday night, the Ministry of External
Affairs said India expected positive response to its initiatives
from the G-8 countries rather than "prescriptive and coercive
suggestions which are neither responsible nor constructive".
</P>
<P>
India had announced a moratorium on further nuclear tests and
its willingness to resume talks with Pakistan on all issues.
</P>
<P>
"Any action on the part of G-8 which does not take these
proposals into account is short-sighted and will be
counter-productive," said the statement.
</P>
<P>
This is the first time the Indian government has preempted
criticism by the international community on its conduct of nuclear
tests four weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that the United States had persuaded Britain to
"widen the scope" of the G-8 meeting so as to magnify the
criticism against India for the nuclear arms race and the
deterioration of situation in South Asia.
</P>
<P>
The statement came in the wake of reports that Britain had
invited "newly converted" states like South Africa, Ukraine and
Brazil to the G-8 foreign ministers meeting in London. 
</P>
</TEXT>
