<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Protest Against Peace Treaty Ends in Bangladesh </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, June 11 (Xinhua) -- The two-day "long march" of
Bangladesh's seven-party opposition alliance, after a nearly
400-kilometer journey, ended on Wednesday afternoon in the
country's southeastern Chittagong Hill Tracts, reports reaching
here Thursday said.
</P>
<P>
The long march, which started from Dhaka on Tuesday, was
organized to press the demand to scrap the peace treaty on the
hill tracts signed between the government and the tribals in
December last year.
</P>
<P>
At a huge public rally at the hill district of Khagrachhari
Wednesday afternoon, opposition leader Begum Kaleda Zia strongly
criticized the accord, which she said had "violated the
Constitution" and "snatched the fundamental and citizenship rights
of the people" in the region.
</P>
<P>
"We want peace and development of this area without taking
recourse to any discrimination," she said, adding, "We want an
agreement that would ensure equal rights and dignity of all. We
wanted to make a law which would establish permanent peace in the
region."
</P>
<P>
The opposition leader announced a dawn-to-dusk hartal across
the country on June 18 to protest against "obstruction of the long
march, price hike of essentials, unabated corruption,
deteriorating law and order and the government's failure to meet
the demand for gas, power and water."
</P>
<P>
She also called for observing a "protest day" on June 22
through demonstration, rallies and processions to protest the
"failure of the autocratic inefficient government in every
sector."
</P>
<P>
Some 70,000 people with about 1,000 vehicles were reportedly to
have participated in marching towards Khagrachhari, and about
10,000 people towards Rangamati, another hill district.
</P>
<P>
The long march was largely peaceful, despite minor clashes
between supporters and opponents before and during the march which
left dozens of people injured, the reports said. There were so far
no reports of casualties.
</P>
<P>
The seven-party alliance includes the BNP, the Jammat-e-Islami,
the Jatiya Party, the Democratic League, the National Democratic
Party, the Progressive Nationalist Party, and the Democratic
Nationalist Alliance. 
</P>
</TEXT>
