<HEADLINE> 16 Percent of Bangladeshis Use Electricity: Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, June 11 (Xinhua) -- At present, only 16 percent of
Bangladesh's 127 million people consume electricity, an English
daily reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
This was stated by Minister Without Portfolio Noor Uddin Khan
(former energy minister) while replying to a question in the
parliament Wednesday, The Daily Star said.
</P>
<P>
Of the total consumers, 579,000 consumers representing 15
percent of the subscribers were commercial subscribers while over
three million representing 79 percent of the total subscribers
were domestic users, the minister told the parliament.
</P>
<P>
The problems relating to load shedding and low voltage had
improved partially following the government's step to close down
shops and markets after 7 p.m. in the country, he added.
</P>
<P>
Bangladesh has a power shortage of 450 megawatts every day
against the minimum nationwide demand for 2,200 megawatts,
according to officials with the Power Development Board.
</P>
<P>
The government has taken a series of steps to streamline the
power generating and supplying system and it is also implementing
several projects in this regard to increase the number of
electricity consumers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
