<DOCNO> XIE19980611.0203 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Chief Justice Refuses to Discuss Lack of Minority </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 10 (Xinhua) -- Randy Jones, president of the
National Bar Association representing 17,000 black lawyers, said
Wednesday he would continue to seek changes in the judicial system
despite Chief Justice William Rehnquist's refusal to discuss the
scarcity of minority law clerks.
</P>
<P>
Jones said black lawyers will continue to try to convince the
chief justice of the usefulness of such discussion.
</P>
<P>
Rehnquist had turned down a request by minority lawyers to
discuss the scarcity of minority law clerks at the Supreme Court,
saying he did not think such a meeting "would serve any useful
purpose".
</P>
<P>
Rehnquist, in a May 27 letter to the president of the nation's
largest organization of black lawyers, said each justice chooses
his or her own clerks, making it an issue beyond his authority.
</P>
<P>
"I have no control, nor would I seek to assert any control,
over the hiring practices of my eight colleagues," Rehnquist wrote.
</P>
<P>
Jones had extended the invitation to Rehnquist on behalf of a
coalition of minority bar association leaders.
</P>
<P>
"This issue is not dead by any means," the Associated Press
quoted Jones as saying from his office in San Diego, California.
"We're hoping to convince him that it would be beneficial both to
the Supreme Court and to the minority law community."
</P>
<P>
Jones said the coalition of minority lawyers began broaching
the lack of minorities clerking at the Supreme Court in March.
The group wanted to find out how it could increase diversity among
the clerks, particularly by learning about the application process
and the qualifications needed to secure the competitive positions.
</P>
<P>
"We think it's in the best interest of justices to have
different viewpoints," Jones said, noting that law clerks often
screen which cases make it to the judges. "To have that branch
aloof from the people is a detriment to the administration of
justice."
</P>
<P>
In March, USA Today said that of the 394 clerks hired by all
nine current justices during their tenures, one percent were
Hispanic, two percent were black and 4.5 percent were Asian. No
Native Americans have served as clerks.
</P>
<P>
Rehnquist said he chooses his three law clerks each year "on
the basis of superior professional achievement in law school,
together with an appraisal as to how well we would work together."
 He added that he has never excluded anyone from consideration
based on race or nationality.
</P>
<P>
In his letter, the chief justice also offered to take
recommendations from the minority lawyers in support of particular
applicants. Jones said that could be a critical first step in
addressing the problem. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980611.0204 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thai Airway Well-Prepared for Millennium Bug </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, June 11 (Xinhua) -- Thai Airway International (Thai)
said it is well-prepared for any problems related to the so-called
"millennium bug," the computer glitch that will make many old
generation computers and software worldwide unworkable after
December 31, 1999.
</P>
<P>
Leading English-language newspaper The Nation reported Thursday
that Thai has sorted out half of the potential complications and
expects to have all the critical areas under control by the end of
this year.
</P>
<P>
The entire exercise is estimated to cost between 200 to 300
million baht (4.65 to 6.98 million U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
About 137 software applications are involved throughout the
airline, all of which have to be identified, investigated, fixed
and tested in a careful, methodical manner that does not disrupt
the day-to-day work.
</P>
<P>
The main priority areas are safety and maintenance of aircraft
and spare parts, and the computer reservation system which has to
be error-free in order to ensure that people, as of January 1,
1999, can reserve flights in the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
In tackling the problem, Thai's 340-strong information
technology staff worked closely with a specially set-up corporate
y2k committee comprising of representatives from the airline's
various departments. 
</P>
