<HEADLINE> Thailand Offers Discount Card to Boost Tourism </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, June 11 (Xinhua) -- Thailand has become the first
country in Asia to offer the Touristcard, which will be marketed
worldwide and offer holders discounts of up to 20 percent, the
Bangkok Post reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
According to the newspaper, discounts will be available at
selected restaurants, tourist attractions and retailers at major
tourist destinations.
</P>
<P>
Micheal Thomas International (MTI), the Asian licensee for
Paris-based Touristcard Co. Ltd., said the company expects 3-4
million card holders in Thailand during the amazing Thailand
campaign in 1998 and 1999.
</P>
<P>
Each card is valid for up to six people a year from the date it
is first issued. Holders can collect points to redeem for extra
gifts.
</P>
<P>
Touristcard has introduced the card successfully in seven
cities in France and is in the process of placing it in other
major tourist destinations in Europe such as London, Rome and
Madrid.
</P>
<P>
There are now 2.5 million card holders worldwide, the company
said.
</P>
<P>
The first participating tourist card retailers in Bangkok will
be announced next week. More members will be signed up in other
tourist destinations such as Chiang Mai, Pattaya, Phuket and Samui
within three months.
</P>
<P>
The card is believed to be helpful for promoting purchasing in
Thailand, since purchasing data will be recorded on the microchip
of the card, which will be valuable for the Tourism Authority of
Thailand (TAT) in terms of developing and marketing attractions.
</P>
<P>
TAT figures showed that shopping accounted for the most
spending by foreign tourists, at about 38 percent of the total.
Last year, tourists spent 89 billion baht (2.07 billion U.S.
dollars) on shopping in Thailand. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
