<HEADLINE> World Bank to Extend New Loans to Thailand </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, June 11 (Xinhua) -- The World Bank is prepared to
offer Thailand an additional 800 million U.S. dollars in loans to
help fund the country's environmental, social development and
industrial programs.
</P>
<P>
The Bangkok Post Thursday quoted J. Shivakunmar, World Bank's
director in Thailand, as saying that the funds would be divided
into two lots, with the first 400 million dollars available in the
first half of 1999 and the second lot in the second half.
</P>
<P>
The funds are designed to strengthen Thailand's industrial
competitiveness in the long-term and help alleviate the social
impact of the economic slump, the director said when signing an
agreement Wednesday with officials from the Fiscal Policy Office
for a separate 400 million dollar loan.
</P>
<P>
Fiscal Policy Office Director-General Sommai Phasee said that
part of the 400 million dollar fund would be used to recapitalize
state financial institutions such as the Bank of Agriculture and
Agricultural Cooperatives, Export-Import Bank, Government Housing
Bank and Government Savings Bank.
</P>
<P>
The remaining funds would be extended to the four banks as soft
loans for relending to the public, Sommai said.
</P>
<P>
The 400 million dollar loan is part of the World Bank's 1.5
billion dollar structural adjustment loans to Thailand under the
International Monetary Fund's 17.2 billion dollar package.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
