<HEADLINE> Controlling Water Discharge In Eastern Chinese Lake </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HEFEI, June 11 (Xinhua) -- Companies operating around Chaohu
Lake in east China's Anhui Province will have to to reach standard
waste water discharge levels by the end of next year,
Vice-governor Zhang Ping announced.
</P>
<P>
Chaohu is China's fifth largest lake and has been on the State
Council's key pollution treatment list. The water quality of
the lake has sharply declined in recent years, due in large part
to the 550,000 tons of waste water discharged each day by
enterprises in the provincial capital, Hefei.
</P>
<P>
To solve this problem, the city government began pollution
treatment projects. A waste water treatment plant with a daily
capacity of 150,000 tons is being built and will go into operation
in the later half of the year, and a quarter of the city's
industrial enterprises are being told that they will have to reach
waste water discharge levels by the end of the year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
