<HEADLINE> Singapore Stresses Drug Prevention </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, June 10 (Xinhua) -- Singapore's preventive drug
education programs have yielded encouraging results with fewer
drug-related arrests in recent years, Singapre's Home Minister
Wong Kan Seng told the U.N. special session on drugs here
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The number of people arrested dropped from 6,160 in 1994 to
4,750 last year, while the number of new addicts fell from 1,420
in 1996 to 1,130 last year, he said.
</P>
<P>
"The drug situation in Singapore is very much under control,"
he claimed.
</P>
<P>
Singapore took the drug problem seriously because its
geographical location put it at constant risk of being used as a
transshipment point for drug trafficking, Wong said.
</P>
<P>
Strict anti-drug laws and effective enforcement also operated
and drug offenders were treated equal regardless of whether they
were citizens of Singapore or other nations, the Minister said.
</P>
</TEXT>
