<DOCNO> XIE19980611.0218 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.N. Concludes Special Session on Drugs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, June 10 (Xinhua) -- The General Assembly of the
United Nations on Wednesday concluded a three-day Special Session
and adopted three documents on fighting the world drug problem.
</P>
<P>
The Special Session, also known as the "Drugs Summit," reviewed
previous policies against the illicit production, sale, demand,
trafficking and distribution of narcotics and psychotropic
substances and proposed new strategies to combat the problem.
</P>
<P>
A Political Declaration adopted at the session calls on member
states to commit themselves to significant and measurable results
in reduction of the illicit supply and demand for drugs by the
year 2008.
</P>
<P>
It also calls for strong domestic laws and programs by 2003 to
deal with such issues as money-laundering and synthetic drugs,
increased drug prevention among the young, and more cooperation
between nations to catch and prosecute drug traffickers.
</P>
<P>
Guiding Principles of Drug-Demand Reduction, another document
adopted at the session, outlines principles to aid governments to
set up new or enhanced programs to reduce demand by 2003.
</P>
<P>
It contains standards to guide governments in setting up
effective prevention, treatment and rehabilitation programs and
calls for the provision of adequate resources for such programs.
</P>
<P>
Measures to Enhance International Cooperation, the third
document, includes action plans to eradicate amphetamine-type
stimulants and their precursors and to promote international
cooperation on the eradication of illicit drug crops and on
alternative development as well as controlling precursors,
promoting judicial cooperation and countering money-laundering.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980611.0219 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-11 </DATE_TIME>
