<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Drug Abuse Grows in Canada, Germany </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, June 10 (Xinhua) -- Canada and Germany, two
developed countries, recognize that their drug abuse problem is
getting serious.
</P>
<P>
Although Canada's climate precludes the cultivation of either
coca bush or opium poppy, it does produce cannabis, and has become
a cannabis exporting country, Canada's Solicitor General Andrew
Scott told the United Nations General Assembly special session on
drugs here on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
"Canada views its drug problem as serious," he said. Cannabis
was the most commonly used illicit drug in the North American
country, followed by cocaine and heroin, with a moderate use of
synthetic drugs.
</P>
<P>
"Canada is experiencing a particularly serious health crisis in
Vancouver with a high level of overdose deaths and one of the
highest rates of HIV infections in developed countries," Scott
said.
</P>
<P>
Taking the floor at the conference, German Foreign Minister
Klaus Kinkel said Wednesday that Germany has seen a steady rise in
the number of first-time users of hard drugs since 1995, with 1997
experiencing a 25 percent growth.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. special session took the drug demand reduction as an
essential part of a balanced approach to the drug problem,
striving for a substantial reduction in ten years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
