<HEADLINE> Clinton Condemns Killing of Black Man in Texas </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 10 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton on
Wednesday denounced that the killing of a black man by three white
men in Texas in a way of torture during the weekend as "shocking
and outrageous."
</P>
<P>
The 49-year black man, James Byrd Jr., was chained to a pickup
truck and dragged to his death in Jasper, Texas, on Sunday. The
body of the black man was torn to pieces and the mangled torso was
found Sunday on a bumpy winding country road about 16 kilometers
from his Jasper home. His severed head, neck and right arm were
about a kilometers away.
</P>
<P>
The killing demonstrated that "an act of evil like this is not
what this country is all about," Clinton said at the opening of a
speech on women's pay equity.
</P>
<P>
Clinton said, "We are determined that the investigation will be
thorough, will be fair, and that the guilty will be brought to
justice."
</P>
<P>
Lawrence Russell Brewer, 31, of Sulphur Springs, and Shawn
Allen Berry and John William King, both 23, of Jasper, were
charged with murder. The three, all with criminal records, are
being held without bail.
</P>
<P>
Investigators said the men have ties to white supremacist
groups and one carried a lighter engraved with an emblem of the Ku
Klux Klan.
</P>
<P>
District Attorney Guy James Gray said in Jasper on Wednesday
that prosecutors are seeking the death penalty against the three
white men. 
</P>
</TEXT>
