<HEADLINE> UN Calls on Member States to Reduce Drug Demand </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, June 10 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations called
on its members states on Wednesday to pledge a sustained
commitment to investing in drug demand reduction programs.
</P>
<P>
The call was contained in a political declaration adopted by
The U.N. special session on the world drug problem. The
declaration outlined the guiding principles for the future
strategies in fighting the world-wide problem.
</P>
<P>
Under the political declaration, the member states would commit
themselves to achieving significant and measurable results in
demand reduction by the year 2008.
</P>
<P>
They will also strengthen efforts against the laundering of
money linked to drug trafficking and against illicit the
cultivation, production, manufacture and trafficking of drugs.
</P>
<P>
In its call for action, the special session said demand
reduction programs should be based on a regular assessment of the
nature and magnitude of drug abuse and drug-related problems.
</P>
<P>
"Drug reduction efforts should be integrated into broader
social welfare and health promotion policies and preventive
education programs," it said.
</P>
<P>
The special session also reiterated its call for interregional
and international cooperation to control the supply and reduce the
demand for drugs. 
</P>
</TEXT>
