<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ADB Provides Loan for Sri Lanka's Wild Life Development </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, June 11 (Xinhua) -- The Asian Development Bank (ADB)
has granted Sri Lanka a loan of 550,000 U.S. dollars for the
conservation of bio-diversity in the country, sources from wild
life departments said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The project proposes the establishment of an effective and
sustainable management of the country's wild life and habitat
resources.
</P>
<P>
A development plan for the implementation of the project is
being prepared by both local and ADB experts, the sources said.
</P>
<P>
Matters under study include the main problems of the conflict
between people and animals, land pressure, inter-departmental
technical management, habitat degradation, conservation education,
poverty and unemployment in areas around national parks and wild
life reserves and sanctuaries, the sources pointed out.
</P>
<P>
The project will concentrate on five protected areas in the
southern and central provinces, inclusive of terrestrial and
marine parks, sanctuaries in wet and dry zones, conservation
forests, contiguous corridors and agricultural land adjacent to
protected areas, the sources added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
