<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Annan Recommends U.N. Mission for Sierra Leone </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, June 10 (Xinhua) -- United Nations
Secretary-General Kofi Annan Wednesday recommended the
establishment of a U.N. observer mission in Sierra Leone to help
disarm the former ruling junta and support the "fragile but vital
process" of promoting civilian rule.
</P>
<P>
In his report to the U.N. Security Council, Annan said the
situation in Sierra Leone has in some respects improved
considerably.
</P>
<P>
However, in the eastern area and parts of the north, remnants
of the former junta continue to resist the Monitoring Group of the
Economic Community of West African States (ECOWAS) and attack
Sierra Leonean civilians, said Annan.
</P>
<P>
He said the mission, known as the United Nations Observer
Mission in Sierra Leone (UNOMSIL), would be composed of 70
observers and led by his Special Envoy in Sierra Leone, with a
mandate of six months, beginning in July 1998.
</P>
<P>
The mission would monitor the military and security situations
in Sierra Leone, assist the government and ECOWAS in disarming the
former ruling junta, monitor progress in the creation of a new
national army, and monitor respect for international humanitarian
law at disarmament and demobilization sites.
</P>
<P>
"Such a deployment at this stage could lead (a) much-needed
impetus to a fragile but vital process, which deserves the support
of the international community," the U.N. chief said.
</P>
<P>
Nigerian-led West African peacekeepers ousted Sierra Leone's
military junta of Lt. Col. Johnny Paul Koroma in February and
restored the elected government of President Ahmed Tejan Kabbah,
who was toppled in a coup in May last year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
