<HEADLINE> Illegal Possession of Firearms Down in Panama </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CITY OF PANAMA, June 10 (Xinhua) -- The illegal possession of
firearms in Panama decreased 16.5 percent in 1997, says report of
the National Criminal Statistics Committee.
</P>
<P>
The report said that in 1997, a total of 709 cases of illegal
possession of firearms were filed, 140 cases less than in 1996.
Most cases were lodged in cities.
</P>
<P>
However, the crime rate kept rising. Police figures show that
during the past eight years, 2,546 cases of homicide perpetrated
with firearms were registered in the central American country.
</P>
