<DOCNO> XIE19980611.0235 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Survey Says Farmland Poorly Used </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 11 (Xinhua) -- A national survey show that
116,500 ha of farmland in China has been left idle or used
inefficiently, and 54 percent of this figure is cultivated land.
</P>
<P>
The survey listed top ten areas for leaving large amount of
land idle as Guangdong, Hainan, Zhejiang, Jiangsu, Fujian,
Shandong, Liaoning and Hunan provinces, Shanghai municipality and
Guangxi Zhuang Autonomous Region.
</P>
<P>
These areas are mostly situated in coastal areas where half of
the country's total arable land is found, noted today's China
Daily.
</P>
<P>
The survey also concluded that half of the arable land left
idle could not be recultivated since the natural conditions for
crop-growing had been destroyed.
</P>
<P>
Seventy percent of the total land left idle was set aside for
construction projects.
</P>
<P>
The survey carried out last year was combined with a national
inspection on the enforcement of State laws regarding land
management in local areas, said the Beijing-based daily.
</P>
<P>
The one-year inspection found more than 3.82 million cases of
illegal use of land.
</P>
<P>
By the end of last October, over 2.1 million of these cases had
been settled. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
