<HEADLINE> U.S. to Set Cableway Compensation Soon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, June 10 (Xinhua) -- The United States will try to set the
compensation it proposes to pay for the victims of the Mount
Cermis cableway disaster "as quickly as possible," the ANSA news
agency reported Wedensday.
</P>
<P>
United States Defense Secretary William Cohen said this Tuesday
after talks with his Italian counterpart, Beniamino Andreatta.
</P>
<P>
Twenty were killed when a U.S. Marine Corps Prowler electronic
surveillance jet sliced through a cableway on Mount Cermis in the
Dolomite Alps, on February 3.
</P>
<P>
The 20 died when the cable car they were traveling in plunged
onto the mountain-side.
</P>
<P>
Court martial proceedings against the crew opened in the U.S.
on April 20, and Cohen said they would proceed "responsibly."
</P>
<P>
He said that if the pilots' commanders were also found to have
responsibilities in the tragedy, they too will have to respond to
charges.
</P>
<P>
Andreatta said the Italian government would do everything in
could to speed up compensation procedures over the 100 million
lire (60,000 U.S. dollars) it had promised the victims. But he
noted that to date only two families had filed all the necessary
paperwork.
</P>
<P>
Andreatta said he had asked military attaches at all Rome
embassies which represented victims countries of origin to contact
the related families and help them complete the needed
documentation to receive, at least, the 100 million lire. 
</P>
</TEXT>
