<HEADLINE> IMF May Resume Aid to Indonesia in July </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, June 11 (Xinhua) -- The International Monetary Fund
(IMF) may resume its aid to Indonesia in early or mid-July,
according to IMF's top man in Asia, quoted by the local press
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The disbursement of the second tranche of Indonesia's bailout
package can only be resumed once the review is complete, said IMF
Asia Pacific Director Hubert Neiss who arrived here Wednesday
night.
</P>
<P>
The IMF put on hold the second disbursement of its 43 billion
U.S. dollar Indonesian aid package amounting to one billion U.S.
dollars because of the recent political turmoil which led to the
resignation of former president Soeharto.
</P>
<P>
The IMF was to have disbursed the aid on June 4.
</P>
<P>
Neiss said the IMF review team, consisting of around 15 people,
started their task when they arrived in Jakarta last Monday.
</P>
<P>
The review team would be in Jakarta for two to three weeks, he
added.
</P>
<P>
On the visit, Neiss said his visit is aimed at reviewing
Indonesia's macroeconomic targets.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, Indonesian State Minister for National Development
Planning Boediono told reporters here Monday that the visit of the
IMF team is not aimed at determining whether or not the IMF will
disburse one billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
"The discussion will focus on macroeconomic targets, banking
affairs, social safety net and the state budget," Boediono said.
</P>
</TEXT>
