<HEADLINE> Pak Reiterates Readiness to Enter Dialogue with India </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, June 10 (Xinhua) -- Pakistan on Wednesday reiterated
that it is prepared to enter into a "serious, constructive and
result-oriented" dialogue with India.
</P>
<P>
"We welcome the renewed interest of the international community
in developments in our region and look forward to working in
partnership to address and resolve all the outstanding issues for
durable peace in South Asia" a Foreign Office spokesman said in a
statement late Wednesday evening.
</P>
<P>
"Pakistan is always prepared to enter into a serious,
constructive and result-oriented dialogue with India," he said.
</P>
<P>
"The international community must engage itself with the
political process, which would, if pursued meaningfully and
seriously, yield positive results both in terms of the
stabilization of the nuclearized South Asia and in finding a just
settlement of the Kashmir issue," he said.
</P>
<P>
He said that Pakistan agrees with the U.N. Security Council
that the Jammu and Kashmir dispute is "a root-cause of tensions in
South Asia which must be addressed to reduce the risk of a
conflagration."
</P>
<P>
"We desire a peaceful settlement of the Jammu and Kashmir
dispute," the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif had already renewed his offer for a
non-aggression pact with India on the basis of a just settlement
of the Kashmir dispute, he added.
</P>
<P>
"Diplomatic steps now must be taken to promote peace and
stability in the region," he said. 
</P>
