<HEADLINE> Investments Drop Sharply in Philippines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, June 11 (Xinhua) -- The economic turmoil in Asia
continued to take its toll on the Philippines as investments in
projects approved by the Board of Investments (BOI) dropped by 43
percent in May to just 18.2 billion pesos (467 million U.S.
dollars) from the year-ago level.
</P>
<P>
In a report published Thursday, the BOI showed that almost all
major investment indicators declined in May.
</P>
<P>
The equity portion of these projects plunged by 67.8 percent to
only 5.4 billion pesos (138.5 million dollars), compared to 16.8
billion pesos (431 million dollars) recorded in the same period
last year.
</P>
<P>
The projects number only 20 compared to 36 projects in the same
month last year.
</P>
<P>
The new investments are also expected to generate only 2,724
employment opportunities, much lower than the estimated 44,386
jobs created by investments approved by the BOI for the same
period last year.
</P>
<P>
The BOI said the country's top investors in May were Canada
with nearly 2 billion pesos (51.3 million dollars), followed by
Norway and Germany. 
</P>
</TEXT>
