<DOCNO> XIE19980611.0256 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Space Technology Brings Fortune to Chinese Farmers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANCHANG, June 11 (Xinhua) -- Zhao Changgeng, a farmer in
Guangchang County in east China's Jiangxi Province, said he never
expected to collect more than 100 kilograms of lotus seeds in a
pond of 0.066 hectares.
</P>
<P>
But that's just what he did with the help of space-bred seeds.
</P>
<P>
In 1994, the local Lotus Institute joined the Chinese Academy
of Sciences in carrying out an experiment on the breeding of lotus
seeds on a space satellite. About 800 lotus seeds were put on the
satellite, which was then launched into orbit.
</P>
<P>
A dozen days later, these seeds were sent back to Guangchang
and planted in 800 vats. One year passed and three seeds were
found mutated and named Space One, Two and Three.
</P>
<P>
Zhao planted the offspring of these seeds and they have brought
him good fortune.
</P>
<P>
"Just imagine, one Mu (0.066 ha.) can yield nearly 100 kilograms
of lotus seeds, an unheard-of figure," he said. "Isn't it a miracle?"
</P>
<P>
Now Zhao, in his 50s, devotes most of his time in his 0.4
hectares of lotus pond, which produces 60 percent of his annual
income.
</P>
<P>
Zhao built a new house and bought a color TV with the money
earned from planting this new lotus variety.
</P>
<P>
The space-bred seeds are high-yielding, said Xie Keqiang,
director of the institute, defining the highest per-hectare yield
to be 1,900 kilograms, 60 percent higher than the original variety.
</P>
<P>
"We are planning to set up another 67 hectares of fine
seed-breeding base, so that more farmers will be able to plant
with the space-bred seeds," said Xie.
</P>
<P>
At present, the space-bred seeds have been planted in about
20,000 hectares of lotus ponds in Guangchang and its neighbouring
region, according to local sources.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980611.0257 </DOCNO>
