<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, June 10 (Xinhua) -- 58 out of 64 matches of World
Cup '98 final round will be televised live, much to the excitement
of Vietnamese football fans, according to an announcement from the
Central Viet Nam Television.
</P>
<P>
A ticket to France World Cup '98 has been merely a dream for
most people in Viet Nam where average per capita income is about
some 250 U.S. dollars a year.
</P>
<P>
A official report here said the Vietnamese people's love for
this fantastic sport is comparable to that of other to ranking
nations in the world even though the Vietnamese national squad was
ranked 125th in FIFA rankings.
</P>
<P>
In an effort to give viewers better pictures of France '98
matches, VTV installed an additional antenna receiver.
</P>
<P>
The French International Channel (CFI) is responsible for
providing live pictures of matches of the global four-year sport
event organized in France's stadiums from June 10 to July 13 to
VTV.
</P>
<P>
Several 300-inch screens have been installed for the first time
in public places in Hanoi and Ho Chi Minh city.
</P>
<P>
Managers of coffee shops, restaurants and hotels in urban areas
throughout the country will not miss this opportunity to promote
their prestige with many of them affording large screen tv sets.
</P>
<P>
In a move to prevent possible negative "social phenomenon"
during the high time, Ho Chi Minh city issued an instruction
providing regulations for leisure facilities in the city to
provide live televised matches at public places.
</P>
<P>
Most of Vietnamese newspapers have devoted large coverage to
carrying reports on France '98 to satisfy local fans' enthusiasm
for the game.
</P>
<P>
Domestic market has been also influenced by this worldwide
sport event. Dealers of tv and sport wear shops are the most
happy.
</P>
<P>
Prices of large-screen tv sets (over 21 inch) have been soaring
in Hanoi and Ho Chi Minh city as World Cup approaches.
</P>
<P>
Restaurants, hotels and clubs have done the same thing to be
ready for the event while police, public transports and store
departments are expecting a specially quiet night. 
