<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Attorney General Asks States to Do Gun Checks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 10 (Xinhua) -- Attorney General Janet Reno on
Wednesday urged states to do their own criminal background checks
of would-be gun buyers when new national gun control rules take
effect this fall.
</P>
<P>
Beginning November 30, all gun purchases from licensed dealers
will be subject to "instant background checks" done on the spot by
computer or phone. States may do the checks, or leave them to the
FBI. Gun dealers will likely pass on the cost of the check to
customers.
</P>
<P>
The Justice Department wants states to do the background checks
to save money at the FBI and to prevent confusion over different
state laws. The FBI plans to charge 13 to 16 dollars per
background check to states that won't do their own.
</P>
<P>
"No one knows more about state records than the states
themselves," Reno said.
</P>
<P>
About half the states have so far agreed to do their own
checks.
</P>
<P>
The National Instant Check System takes effect November 30 as
part of the 1993 Brady Act. The law set up a five-day waiting
period for handgun purchases and also required establishment of a
national system to perform instant checks.
</P>
<P>
The instant checks, which replace the waiting period, are
supposed to weed out felons and others not entitled to buy guns.
</P>
<P>
The system is designed to handle up to 15,000 requests an hour.
About 80 percent of the time, the would-be buyer will get
immediate approval, a Justice Department official said.
</P>
<P>
The system will link the FBI with more than 60,000 gun dealers
nationwide.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980611.0263 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: African Leaders Heading for Strong </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OUAGADOUGOU, June 10 (Xinhua) -- Conflicts, both real and
potential, are remaining to be the top threat to peace and
stability in Africa.
</P>
<P>
The economic growth Africa has attained in recent years is
still fragile, mostly because of this reason.
</P>
<P>
Despite this harsh fact, leaders across the continent, who
have just concluded a continental summit Wednesday, do not seem
pessimistic about the future of Africa.
</P>
<P>
The 34th summit of the Organization of African Unity (OAU)
served as a forum for the leaders to renew their commitment to
build a politically and economically strong Africa in the next
millennium, said President Blaise Compaore of Burkina Faso, who
has chaired the meeting for the past three days.
</P>
<P>
Instead of being a social gathering of African Heads of State
and Government, a saying rejected by Ghanaian President Jerry
Rawlings, the summit has done a lot in this regard.
</P>
<P>
At the end of the summit, the leaders approved all the 31
resolutions submitted by OAU's Council of Ministers, and adopted
the Ouagadougou Declaration and two decisions on the political
and economic situation in Africa.
</P>
<P>
Issues concerning peace and stability in the continent
dominated the summit.
</P>
<P>
Following heated debate and discussions, the leaders of OAU
member states urged Ethiopia and Eritrea "to put an end to all
hostilities at the same time and simultaneously" so as to prevent
the conflict from escalation.
</P>
<P>
About 50 civilians, including school kids, were reportedly
killed and some 150 wounded during the air raids the two Horn of
African countries launched against each other last week.
</P>
<P>
The Ethiopian-Eritrean conflict, escalated from border
dispute, erupted when African leaders have just breathed a sigh
of relief with the improvement in the situation in Sierra Leone,
Liberia, Burundi and some other parts of the continent.
</P>
<P>
The leaders, deeply concerned over the conflict, decided that
host President and new OAU Chairman Blaise Compaore leave within
one week for the Horn of Africa at the head of a delegation to
find a peaceful solution.
</P>
<P>
Another major decision made at the summit is the commitment by
the leaders to enhancing the effectiveness of the central organ
of OAU's conflict prevention, management and resolution
mechanism, aiming at seeking peace and stability for the world's
poorest continent.
</P>
<P>
However, the establishment of an all-African peace keeping
force, which had been widely expected before the summit, did not
appear on the agenda of the leaders who worked together here in
the past three days.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
