<HEADLINE> IDB Finances Geothermal Plant in Costa Rica </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 10 (Xinhua) -- The Inter-American Development
Bank Wednesday announced the approval of loans totaling 49.35
million U.S. dollars equivalent to help finance a 27 megawatt
geothermal plant in Costa Rica.
</P>
<P>
This is the first private sector energy project in the country
to be built on the basis of a contract awarded through competitive
bidding.
</P>
<P>
The project is also the first one in the country under the
terms of a 1995 law designed to encourage private investment in
the energy sector.
</P>
<P>
The IDB financing is made up of a 16.45 million dollar loan
from the Bank's ordinary capital and a syndicated loan of 32.9
million dollars.
</P>
<P>
The project company, Geoenergia de Guanacaste, Limitada, is
investing some 16.45 million dollars in equity.
</P>
<P>
The power plant, located in a geothermal field in the province
of Guanacaste in northwestern Costa Rica, will sell its entire
electricity to the Instituto Costarricense de Electricidad under a
15-year power purchase agreement. 
</P>
</TEXT>
