<HEADLINE> Clinton Orders Sanctioning Belgrade </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 10 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton on
Wednesday ordered to freeze Serbian assets in the U.S. and ban
investments in that country because of its crackdown on Kosovo
Albanians.
</P>
<P>
The Contact Group, comprising of Germany, France, Britain,
Italy, Russia and the United States, decided to impose the
sanctions last month but suspended it after Belgrade agreed to
talk with the Albanian separatists in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
On Monday, the State Department announced the decision to
reimpose sanctions because of the recent escalating violence in
the region.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a regular briefing on Wednesday, State Department
spokesman James Rubin said the U.S. is seeking to arrange
confidence-building measures in Kosovo as a precondition to
resuming talks between Serbia and the separatists.
</P>
<P>
Such measures, he said, could include security guarantees for
the ethnic Albanians, the return of refugees and an agreement to
station observers in the province, where Serbian troops have
launched an offensive to crush separatist sentiment.
</P>
<P>
Washington was in touch with the Kosovo Albanians and the
Serbians with a view to resuming the dialogue, according to Rubin.
The two sides were to have met again last week but the meeting was
called off by the Albanians.
</P>
<P>
"We want to establish a situation where both sides recognize
the solution is at the negotiating table, not on the battlefield,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that the "best way to do that" is Belgrade offers
"a credible confidence and security building plan" that will give
the Kosovar Albanians new confidence and new assurances.
</P>
<P>
"The Kosovar Albanians have indicated... that to talk in the
absence of a confidence and security building plan and in the
presence of this kind of onslaught is simply untenable. And we
certainly understand that," Rubin said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
