<HEADLINE> Lebanon, Bulgaria Sign Cooperation Protocols </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, June 10 (Xinhua) -- Lebanon and Bulgaria Wednesday
signed two cooperation protocols in diplomatic and cultural fields.
</P>
<P>
The documents were signed here by visiting Bulgarian Foreign
Minister Nadezhda Mikhailova and her Lebanese counterpart Farez
Boueiz, the National News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
After the signing ceremony, Boueiz said at a joint news
conference with Mikhailova that the two countries should set the
private sector as a key area for bilateral cooperation.
</P>
<P>
"From now on, we begin to study the possibility to sign other
cooperation agreements such as accords on avoiding double
taxation and protecting investments between the countries," he
added.
</P>
<P>
From her part, Mikhailova expressed hopes to boost cooperation
ties with Lebanon, especially in the economic aspect, saying the
two countries can be complementary in many fields.
</P>
<P>
She said her country for the first time in the history
witnessed a 4 percent of gross domestic product growth this year
and the foreign exchange reserves also for the first time reached
24 billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
She added all these achievements provided a strong base for
cooperations between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
On south Lebanon issue, the Bulgarian minister said that her
country supports the full implementation of the United Nations
resolution 425 and other international resolutions which will lead
to a solution for the Israeli-Arab conflicts.
</P>
<P>
The 20-year-old resolution calls for an unconditional and
immediate Israeli withdrawal from south Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
Mikhailova came here on Tuesday on a two-day visit. She is the
first Bulgarian foreign minister to visit Lebanon since the
establishment of diplomatic ties between the two countries in
1966. 
</P>
</TEXT>
