<DOCNO> XIE19980611.0273 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> OAU to Set Up Fund for AIDS Control </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OUAGADOUGOU, June 10 (Xinhua) -- African leaders have decided
to establish an African fund for AIDS control to deal with the
worsening AIDS situation in the continent.
</P>
<P>
The decision was made at the just-ended 34th summit of heads
of state and government of the Organization of African Unity
(OAU) after taking into full consideration the serious AIDS
situation and the decisions made in the Dakar declaration on the
AIDS epidemic in Africa (1992) and the Tunis declaration on AIDS
and the child in Africa (1994).
</P>
<P>
The summit expressed full support to the proposal put forward
by the republic of Cote d'Ivoire to establish a solidarity fund
to help treatment of patients from Africa and urged the OAU
Secretary-General to pursue this proposal with the government of
Cote d'Ivoire and concerned agencies and report to the next
summit.
</P>
<P>
However, the summit did not elaborate on details concerning
the fund and rules and regulations will be worked out later.
</P>
<P>
The summit requested the international community to adequately
consider Africa in the global resources available for HIV/AIDS in
order to facilitate prevention and wider accessibility to current
research findings, especially on drugs and other medicines
necessary in the overall responses to this infection.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, the African leaders also urged the
international community, especially the pharmaceutical companies
manufacturing anti-retroviral and other drugs necessary in the
management of HIV/AIDS patients to consider wider accessibility
to those drugs by lowering their retail prices.
</P>
<P>
Since 1985 when the first cases of AIDS were reported in
Africa, the situation in most of the African countries has
worsened and by the year 2000, the continent will have as many as
14 million infected adults and up to 40 million infected children
including 10 million orphans.
</P>
<P>
The social and economic consequences of AIDS have been shown
already to be placing a severe strain on the weak economies of
most of African nations especially those in central, eastern and
southern Africa.
</P>
<P>
Even if there were no further infections, the trauma of deaths
of those already infected will continue for the next 20 years,
and the economic and social repercussions will persist for
generations, OAU Secretary-General Salim Ahmed Salim said during
the summit. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
