<HEADLINE> Suspects on Rwandan Genocide Caught in W. Africa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, June 10 (Xinhua) -- U. N. International Criminal
Tribunal for Rwanda (ICTR) said Wednesday that six Rwandans
allegedly involved in the 1994 Rwanda genocide were arrested in
west Africa last week.
</P>
<P>
Prosecutor Louise Arbour said in a statement reaching here
that the authorities of Benin, Cote d'Ivoire and Togo arrested
the accused on June 5 and 7 at his request.
</P>
<P>
The move is "the result of the continuing strategy adopted a
year ago to investigate and prosecute persons responsible for
crimes within the jurisdiction of the ICTR and who held positions
of leadership in Rwanda during 1994," said Arbour.
</P>
<P>
Among them are Mathieu Ngirumpatse, President of the National
Revolutionary Movement for Development (MRND) party which held
power at the start of the genocide, and his top aid Edouard
Karamera who was also the interior minister in the interim
government that ruled during the killings.
</P>
<P>
Others are Emmanuel Bagambiki, former Prefect of Cyangugu,
Joseph Nzirorera, former President of the National Assembly and
MRND Secretary-General, Juvenal Kajelijeli, a former senior
official, as well as Omar Serushago, a local military leader.
</P>
<P>
It was estimated over 500,000 Tutsis and moderate Hutus were
killed during the 1994 genocide.
</P>
<P>
Local reports said they would be transferred to the ICTR
headquarters based in northern Tanzanian town of Arusha soon.
</P>
<P>
The tribunal has so far indicted a total of 36 people on the
Rwandan genocide, 25 of them in custody in Arusha. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
