<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, June 10 (Xinhua) -- Malawi has called on Southern
African Development Community (SADC) member states to integrate
their management efforts to overcome water scarcity in the
region, the Malawi News Agency (MANA) said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
MANA quoted Malawian Minister of Water Development Edward
Bwanali as saying that the lack of integrated efforts in the
sub-region is counterproductive in the task of achieving the
objectives of the SADC's water sector.
</P>
<P>
"We should recognize as an immediate goal the need to
collectively achieve success and overcome this prevalent water
scarcity," Bwanali told a sectoral committee meeting of senior
SADC water sector officials in Malawian capital Lilongwe.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that water is a vital component for the
region's social and economic development, MANA reported in a
dispatch sent to Xinhua based in Nairobi.
</P>
<P>
"The region's socio-economic development is being threatened
by prevalent water scarcity, degradation, depletion, exploitation
and conflict of interests which also result from lack of
integrated requirements," said Bwanali.
</P>
<P>
He added that water is the "backbone of economic development
within the SADC."
</P>
<P>
Therefore, he said, "Let's do justice to ourselves by
critically assessing all the proposals on integrated water
resources management at national and regional levels." 
