<HEADLINE> Iran, Kuwait Sign MOU on Security Cooperation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, June 10 (Xinhua) -- Iranian Interior Minister Abdollah
Nouri and his visiting Kuwaiti counterpart Sheikh Mohammad Khaled
al-Sabah signed here Wednesday a memorandum of understanding (MOU)
to expand security cooperation.
</P>
<P>
The two sides agreed to cooperate in fighting organized crimes,
such as drug production and trafficking, counterfeiting of
government documents and banknotes, and other forms of economic
crimes.
</P>
<P>
They pledged to conduct coordinated efforts in combating the
trafficking of antiques and arts, weaponry and explosives and in
preventing illegal border crossings by citizens of both countries.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, both sides agreed to speed up issuance of visas,
exchange police information and share experiences in prosecution
of wanted criminals.
</P>
<P>
Al-Sabah arrived here Tuesday on a three-day visit. He on
Wednesday also met with Iranian President Mohammad Khatami, who
called for regional cooperation to maintain security and
tranquillity.
</P>
<P>
"Today the region more than any other time is in need of
security and tranquillity, and through cooperation and prudence
of all the regional countries, we should remove any causes of
tension in the region," Khatami said.
</P>
<P>
He said that there was no obstacle in the way of expanding the
brotherly relations between Iran and Kuwait, adding that "we hope
that these relations serve as a model for cooperation throughout
the region."
</P>
<P>
On his part, al-Sabah said that the friendly and brotherly
relations between the two countries have historical roots and the
Kuwaiti government attaches special importance to all-around
expansion of its ties with Iran.
</P>
<P>
He termed security and tranquillity as the primary requirement
for the development of countries in the region, adding that the
Iranian-Kuwaiti agreements on boosting political and security
cooperation would also help enhance bilateral economic cooperation
as well as regional security. 
</P>
</TEXT>
