<BODY>
<HEADLINE> W. African States Mourn Abacha's Death </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, June 10 (Xinhua) -- West African countries have
declared days of national mourning for late Nigerian Head of
State General Sani Abacha who died of a heart attack early
Monday, according to local media reports Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The Ghanaian government late Tuesday announced three days of
national mourning for Abacha, according to a statement of the
Foreign Ministry, which said that all flags across the country
will fly at half mast until Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Togo, who along with Nigeria in 1975 initiated the formation
of the sub-regional body, the Economic Community of West African
States (ECOWAS), has also declared a three-day national mourning.
</P>
<P>
Liberia, which owes greatly to the contribution of Abacha as
ECOWAS Chairman for the ending of its seven years of civil war,
observed a one-day national mourning Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Sierra Leonean President Ahmed Tejan Kabbah, who resumed his
office in March thanks to ECOWAS peace keeping force led by
Nigeria, arrived in Nigerian capital Abuja Tuesday to condole
with the new leader, General Abdusalam Abubakar on the death of
Abacha.
</P>
<P>
Gambian President Yayah Jammah, Nigerien President
Mainassarawa Barre, Chadian President Idris Derby and President
Felix-Ange Patessi of the Central African Republic were all at
Abuja Tuesday to pay their condolences, according to media
reports. 
</P>
