<HEADLINE> Kim Dae-jung Appeals for Investment in South Korea </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 10 (Xinhua) -- South Korean President Kim
Dae-jung said Wednesday that American investors can yield big
rewards if they invest in South Korea and buy its companies'
stocks.
</P>
<P>
"Korea will become one of the best countries for international
investors to freely and safely do business," Kim told a joint
meeting of the House and Senate. "This is a precious opportunity.
And we must seize it."
</P>
<P>
During his half-hour speech, Kim gently prodded the
Republican-led Congress to do more to help the International
Monetary Fund replenish its accounts, badly strained by the Asian
economic crisis.
</P>
<P>
The administration's 18 billion dollar IMF bill has been
stalled in Congress for two months, mostly over unrelated issues.
</P>
<P>
"The IMF is to international finance what the Federal Reserve
is to your nation's financial system -- the lender of last
resort," Kim said. "And the IMF deserves continued support."
</P>
<P>
Kim said his country needs help from the United States so that
South Korea could come out of financial abyss.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, Kim made a similar appeal to business leaders here,
urging them to invest in South Korea and buy its companies'
stocks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
