<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> OAU Summit Speaks for Libya </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OUAGADOUGOU, June 10 (Xinhua) -- African leaders who ended a
summit here Wednesday called again for the lift of sanctions
imposed by the United Nations Security Council on Libya.
</P>
<P>
The sanctions has created immense human and material losses to
the Libyan people and nationals of other member states of the
Organization of African Unity (OAU), according to a decision
adopted at the summit.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. Security Council was recommended to soften its stance
so that Libyans and their leaders as well could fly out of the
country for humanitarian and religious activities, said OAU
Secretary-General Salim Ahmed Salim at a press conference at the
end of the summit.
</P>
<P>
African countries respect the resolutions of the U.N. Security
Council, but they will not comply any longer with that two
resolutions numbered 748 (1992) and 883 (1993) respectively if
the United States and Britain refuse to accept that the two
Libyan suspects of the 1988 bombing of Pan-American Flight 103
over Lockerbie, Scotland, be tried in a third neutral country, he
said.
</P>
<P>
"OAU and its members will not comply from now on with the
sanctions imposed against Libya related to religious obligations,
providing humanitarian emergencies or fulfilling OAU statutory
obligations," the decision says.
</P>
<P>
The leaders also expressed regret for lack of positive
response by the U.S. and Britain to the international and
national initiatives and efforts aiming at finding a solution to
the dispute.
</P>
<P>
The two Western countries have insisted that the two Libyan
suspects be tried in the two countries.
</P>
<P>
The International Court of Justice has confirmed its
competence to look into the dispute, which has been welcomed by
African countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
