<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-10 19:32 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Greek President to Visit Cyprus </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, June 10 (Xinhua) -- Greek President Costis
Stephanopoulos will visit Cyprus later this month amid tensions
on the island just two months before Russian missiles will be
delivered.
</P>
<P>
Announcing the visit Wednesday, Cypriot Foreign Minister
Ioannis Kasoulides described it, scheduled for June 25-28
as "important," pointing out that "this is the first official
visit of a head of the Greek state since the birth of the
Republic of Cyprus in 1960."
</P>
<P>
Kasoulides said it shows Greece's unconditional support to the
Cyprus cause for justice.
</P>
<P>
During his four-day visit, Stephanopoulos is expected to hold
talks with President Glafcos Clerides. He will also have meetings
with President of the House of Representatives Spyros Kyprianou
and the Primate of the Orthodox Church of Cyprus Archbishop
Chrysostomos.
</P>
<P>
The Greek president will also visit the Greek Military
Contingent Forces, stationed in Cyprus in accordance with the
1960 Treaty for the establishment of the Republic of Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
Stephanopoulos' visit comes just two months before the
Russian-made S-300 anti-aircraft missiles, purchased by the
Cypriot government last year, will be delivered.
</P>
<P>
Turkey has repeatedly threatened to strike at the missiles if
they are deployed.
</P>
<P>
Greece, Cyprus' strong supporter, signed a joint defense pact
with Cyprus in 1993, under which Greece will provide military
assistance if Cyprus is attacked.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has remained divided since 1974 when Turkey landed its
troops and took over the northern third of the island in the
aftermath of a failed pro-Athens coup in Nicosia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
