<HEADLINE> Middle East Economic Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, June 10 (Xinhua) -- The following are economic briefs
from Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
ANKARA -- The Organization for Economic Cooperation and
Development (OECD) has stated in its latest 1998 economic report
that the Turkish government's anti-inflation policy was
encouraging, Turkish Daily News reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The OECD said that inflation in Turkey would continue its
downward trend through next year as a result of a monetary policy
designed to decrease borrowing.
</P>
<P>
Although freezing public sector price hikes has not been very
influential in lowering the rate of inflation so far, the OECD
report predicts that inflation may fall to 65 percent in 1999.
</P>
<P>
Turkish inflation rate reached about 80 percent in 1997.
</P>
<P>
DAMASCUS -- Damascus will host the four-day eighth Arab
conference on the industrial development to be organized by the
Arab Industrial Development and Mining Organization on June 22.
</P>
<P>
In remarks to Wednesday's Arabic Al Hayat newspaper, Talat Ibn
Zafir, the organization's assistant director, said the
participants will discuss 32 working papers on the challenges
facing the Arab industry and a working paper on international
changes and means to upgrade the standing industries.
</P>
<P>
AMMAN -- German and Jordan signed three agreements Tuesday,
under which German will provide the kingdom with 5.5 million
U.S. dollars to fund various projects in Jordan.
</P>
<P>
The money will be mainly used to finance the work of German
experts in Jordan, support the kingdom's watershed management and
develop pest control methods, Jordan's official news agency
reported. 
</P>
</TEXT>
