<HEADLINE> Iran's Moderate Newspaper Jame'e Banned </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, June 10 (Xinhua) -- The Tehran public court Wednesday
revoked the publication license of the moderate daily newspaper
Jame'e (society), which has so far released 87 issues, Iranian
official news agency IRNA reported.
</P>
<P>
The court also banned the daily's license holder and managing
director Hamid Reza Jalaiepour from working in a similar position
for one year.
</P>
<P>
Jalaiepour was also fined 16 million rials (about 2,857
U.S. dollars), the IRNA said without mentioning the charges
against the daily and its managing director.
</P>
<P>
Earlier reports said commander of the Islamic Revolution's
Guards Corps (IRGC) Yahya Rahimi Safavi accused the daily, which
started its publication about three months ago, of revealing his
secret speech and insulting the IRGC and himself.
</P>
<P>
In April, Safavi reportedly warned to crack down on a wave of
internal dissent and criticism in a meeting with the IRGC navy
commanders. His speech was interpreted as a warning to the
moderates and their newspapers, who strongly criticized Safavi for
his hard-line remarks.
</P>
<P>
However, the IRGC later stated that Safavi's speech was
distorted by the print mass media.
</P>
<P>
The ban on the moderate daily coincided with the open trial on
Tehran Mayor Gholamhussein Karbaschi and a demand of impeachment
of the Interior Minister Abdollah Nouri.
</P>
<P>
Local observers noted that the ban on Jame'e and the trial on
Karbaschi would pose a serious blow to the moderates, main
supporters of the government of President Mohammad Khatami.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
