<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Brazil Struggle to 2-1 Win over Scotland </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
SAINT DENIS, June 10 (Xinhua) -- Defending champions Brazil
needed a huge share of luck today to beat underdogs Scotland 2-1 in
the opening game of the World Cup finals.
</P>
<P>
An own goal from Tommy Boyd at the 73rd minute lifted the
Brazilian team to the victory.
</P>
<P>
The four-time world champions controlled much of the game but
failed to display their spark and flare of traditional Brazilian
football.
</P>
<P>
Cafu came free in front of the net only to have his shot blocked
by the face of goalkeeper Jim Leighton. But the ball rebounded off
the upper body of Boyd and settled into the net.
</P>
<P>
Boyd, a 32-year-old defender from Celtic, said after the
match:"It is not the kind of goal I like to score. The ball broke
from midfield and one of their guys hit it and Jimmy made a great
save and it hit off my chest and there was nothing I could do to get
out of the way."
</P>
<P>
"It's probably the worst feeling I have ever had in football,"
said John Collins, who last scored an own goal againstAberdeen three
years ago.
</P>
<P>
Collins said:"Brazil snatched it. That is fate for you and that
is the way things go for Scotland in the World Cup."
</P>
<P>
Ronaldo played superbly, particularly in the first half. He set
up Rivaldo with a dummy and then created a chance for Leonardo with
a backheel. He also displayed his magical dribbling skills and
threatened the Scottish goal with his shots several times.
</P>
<P>
However, the Brazilian team looked uninspired and Scotland
looked set to clinch a point when the disaster struck. 
</P>
</TEXT>
