<DOCNO> XIE19980611.0301 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Albright: Tests Bring High Risk of Disaster to South Asia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 10 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright said on Wednesday that the risk of disaster in
South Asia is high following nuclear tests by India and Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
"For both nations, the strategic environment is now far more
complicated and grave. Both face the prospect of an arms race
neither can afford. Each faces the risk of nuclear missiles
being pointed at their cities," Albright told a group of
non-proliferation experts at Henry L. Stimson Center.
</P>
<P>
"Neither can be confident it will have early warning of what
the other will do. And the risk of misinformation leading to
miscalculation, leading to disaster, is high," she added.
</P>
<P>
Albright said the payoff for exploding nuclear devices by
India and Pakistan is "mutual insecurity, decreased prosperity,
a harvest of fear at home and condemnation abroad."
</P>
<P>
She called on leaders in New Delhi and Islamabad "to forswear
any future tests and to refrain from deploying nuclear weapons
or from testing missiles capable of delivering them."
</P>
<P>
She also urged both countries to join the Comprehensive Test
Ban Treaty without conditions.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
