<HEADLINE> Britain Warns of Possible Military Action on Kosovo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, June 10 (Xinhua) -- British Prime Minister Tony Blair
issued a stark warning Wednesday that military action might be
needed to resolve the worsening Kosovo crisis.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at British parliament Wednesday afternoon, Blair said
that Britain was attempting to get support from other countries to
press Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic to resolve the Kosovo
crisis by peaceful means.
</P>
<P>
"The only circumstance in which we will ensure that President
Milosevic responds to diplomatic pressure is if that is backed up
by the threat, the credible threat, of the use of military force,"
Blair said.
</P>
<P>
Blair, who has just finished a whistle-stop tour of other 14
European Union (EU) countries, noted that Britain had been working
"to get the necessary support for that course of action".
</P>
<P>
"If we can do that, then of course we will be in a position to
make that diplomacy work, and if that diplomacy fails, then we
should be in a position to take the military action necessary," he
added.
</P>
<P>
Foreign ministers from the Contact Group countries including
the United States, Russia, Germany, France, Italy and Britain will
meet in London on Friday to discuss how to defuse the Kosovo
crisis.  
</P>
