<HEADLINE> Laos Reduces Opium Production </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, June 10 (Xinhua) -- Laos has managed to reduce
its opium production from 140 tons in 1996 to 126 tons last year,
Vice Foreign Minister Soubanh Srithrath said here on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
He told the on-going U.N. special session on drugs that his
country has made a ten-year 81-million U.S. dollar alternative
development and drug crops reduction plan in cooperation with the
U.N. Drug Control Program (UNDCP).
</P>
<P>
Laos is launching a new national opium production and
consumption survey in 11 of its northern provinces with an aim to
provide a strong basis for future planning and monitoring of drug
related projects.
</P>
<P>
Laos, a member of a Southeast Asia drug control scheme
involving also Cambodia, China, Myanmar, Thailand, Vietnam and
UNDCP, is in close regional cooperation in anti-drug efforts, he
added.  
