<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Scientists Solve A Long-Standing Mystery about The Sun </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, June 10 (Xinhua) -- A clash of magnetic fields is
likely to explain why the Sun's outer atmosphere is much hotter
than its surface, researchers said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
For more than half a century, scientists have been puzzled by
the fact that the surface of the Sun is barely 6,000 degrees
Centigrade, while that of its outer atmosphere scorches up to
several million degrees.
</P>
<P>
A new discovery, made by the research team led by Professor
Eric Priest of St Andrews University in Scotland, together with
scientists in Britain, France and the United States, have partly
solved this long-standing mystery.
</P>
<P>
The scientists believed that a clash of magnetic field lines,
tangling like spaghetti, is causing heating of gigantic and
super-hot loops that extend high up over the Sun's surface into
its outer atmosphere, thus producing the extreme temperature.
</P>
<P>
It is the first time that scientist are able to measure how the
temperature varies along such giant loops by using the Soft X-ray
Telescope on a space satellite called Yohkoh, according to a press
release from St Andrews University.
</P>
<P>
The researchers will detail their findings in a letter to the
scientific journal Nature of 11th June, the press release said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980611.0311 </DOCNO>
