<HEADLINE> Greece's New International Airport to be Open in 2001 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, June 10 (Xinhua) -- Greece's new international airport
for the capital city of Athens will be open on March 1, 2001, a
Greek government official announced Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Speaking during his tour to the airport worksite, Greek Public
Works Minister Costas Laliotis said that the time scale for the
construction of the Eleftherios Venizelos airport was being
strictly adhered to.
</P>
<P>
The new airport at Spata, east of Athens, which has a budget of
658 billion drachmas (about 2.1 billion U.S. dollars), will have a
capacity of 16 million passengers annually.
</P>
<P>
More than 88 percent of the airport's earthworks have
reportedly been completed, and construction of the main terminal,
air traffic control center and control tower is underway.
</P>
<P>
The airport's two runways, each about four kilometers long and
60 meters wide, are expected to handle up to 600 simultaneous
take-offs and landings a day.  
