<HEADLINE> UK Likely to Review Compensation for Ex-POWs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, June 10 (Xinhua) -- British Prime Minister Tony Blair
promised here Wednesday that his government would consider whether
to demand more compensation from Japan for former British
prisoners of war (POWs).
</P>
<P>
Blair reportedly made the promise after meeting leaders of
groups representing the war veterans who maintain that it was not
too late to make such a claim.
</P>
<P>
Mark Oaten, chairman of an all-party parliamentary group of MPs
which looks after the interests of the war veterans, told
reporters that the 40-minute meeting marked "a significant change
in the government's position".
</P>
<P>
Martyn Day, the lawyer advising the POWs groups, said: "The
government clearly has the political will to put the case to the
Japanese government if they are satisfied about the law."
</P>
<P>
The British government had previously ruled out the possibility
of demanding more compensations from Japan on the grounds that
Britain had accepted final compensation terms from Japan in the
1950s.
</P>
<P>
An opinion poll, which was carried out by the war veterans,
revealed that 76 percent of British people believed the veterans
should receive full compensation and a formal apology from Japan.
</P>
</TEXT>
