<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Navy to Face Pilot Shortage </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 10 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. Navy could soon face
pilot shortage as the Air Force do partly because of increased
hiring by commercial airlines and operational stress, the Navy's
top admiral said on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Admiral Jay Johnson, chief of naval operations, told reporters
the Navy was moving quickly to boost pilot retention and avoid a
shortfall expected within two years.
</P>
<P>
The Air Force said last week that it has a shortage of several
hundred pilots and operational stress could leave the service
2,000 short of the required number of pilots in two years.
</P>
<P>
The service is facing unplanned operational tensions because
its pilots are now being increasingly deployed with 90-day Air
Expeditionary Forces to the Gulf and other trouble spots around
the world.
</P>
<P>
Johnson said that the Navy appeared to have a pilot retention
advantage over the Air Force because its aviators have been
traditionally required to make annual six-months deployments at
sea with carrier battle groups.
</P>
<P>
But he said that when large numbers of Navy pilots are promoted
to higher, nonflying ranks over the next two years, the service
will have to increase recruiting rates for pilots by up to 10
percent.
</P>
<P>
Last week, Air Force General Richard Hawley, chief of the Air
Combat Command, called for additional cuts in U.S. air power in
the Gulf near Iraq, citing stress on American personnel and the
ability to dispatch warplanes quickly to threaten Iraq in any new
crisis.
</P>
<P>
The United States has recently announced a reduction of its
military presence in the Gulf region to maintain some 200
warplanes and one aircraft carrier, the level before a major
build-up over U.N. arms inspections in Iraq.
</P>
<P>
But Hawley said that operational stress was mounting in the
shrinking Air Force because of growing deployments to world
trouble spots and that even deeper cuts could be made in the Gulf
for now.
</P>
<P>
Some 5,000 Air Force personnel were currently deployed in
temporary overseas assignments and it caused extra work in
U.S.-based units providing the deployed fliers and ground crews,
said Hawley.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
